<item>
  <title>The Build Up.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2012/06/28/thebuildu/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 28 Jun 2012 16:56:29 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=1</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-family:helvetica;">It has been years that I have run the idea of starting a blog, but the lackluster me never did it. Â Here it is! Â I shall be highlighting my past, present and future travels and then some!</span>

<span style="font-family:helvetica;">I will start with a piece of my trip to my favorite destination, <strong>Iceland</strong>, circa fall 2010<strong>! Â </strong>I say a piece because I took over eight-hundred photos while here. Â The country captivated me before I ever set foot there, so you could only imagine the feeling while being there. Â Imagine. Â While in Iceland, I made a point to Â visit the Imagine Peace Tower onÂ ViÃ°ey Island, right offÂ ReykjavÃ­k. ViÃ°ey Island island is accessed through a short boat ride from ReykjavÃ­k. The Imagine Tower was envisioned by Yoko Ono and built for my favorite Beatle, John Lennon. Â The tower is lit each year from October 9th, John Lennon's birthday, until December 8th, the day of his untimely death.</span>
<p style="text-align:center;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/imaginepeace-1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-14 size-full" title="Imagine Peace Tower, ViÃ°ey Island, Iceland" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/imaginepeace-1.jpg" alt="" width="2866" height="1924" /></a></p>
<span style="font-family:helvetica;">DowntownÂ ReykjavÃ­k provides the backdrop to the Imagine Tower. Â The tower itself is geo-thermally powered while the base holds the words "Imagine Peace" engraved on it in twenty-four different languages. The presence of the tower is serene and peaceful.
</span>

<span style="font-family:helvetica;">Accompanying the tower are Yoko Ono's "Wish Trees." Â You write your wish on a card and tie it to the tree.Â </span>

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/wishtree.jpg"><img class="wp-image-15 size-full" title="Wish Tree" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/wishtree.jpg" alt="" width="2896" height="1944" /></a>

<span style="font-family:helvetica;">Â There is also the second oldest church in Iceland on this island.</span>
<p style="text-align:left;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/videychurch.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-16 size-full" title="ViÃ°ey Church" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/videychurch.jpg" alt="" width="2896" height="1944" /></a>There is more to ViÃ°ey Island island than this. It is a great place to go hiking in the day! There is the Videyjarstofa house where you can devour in an Icelandic Christmas feast if it is around that time of year.</p>
<p style="text-align:left;">The only time I spent on the island was to visit the Imagine Tower. It is a very peaceful place.</p>
<p style="text-align:center;"></p>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>About</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/about/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 28 Jun 2012 16:56:29 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?page_id=2</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/img_8543_2.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-807 aligncenter" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/me.jpg?w=300" alt="me" width="300" height="300" /></a>

Jante Ziarra is a journalism student with a minor in web design, currently living in Long Beach, California. She was born withÂ a passion for food in Ewa Beach (Hawai'i), developedÂ soles for wandering cities in Chicago, and found her place amongst nature in Seattle.

She can't quite stay in one place, which is why she just went on a solo backpacking trip this summer and made it to 15 countries in two months.Â Her camera is almost always with her and if not, that's what the iPhone 6 is for! While exploring, she loves immersing herself in the culture of others, especially through food &amp; beer.

She isÂ <strong>Always Somewhere.Â </strong><strong>Never Nowhere.</strong>
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/img_8543_2.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1024 aligncenter" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/img_8543_2.jpg?w=300" alt="Explore." width="300" height="300" /></a>
Join me on my adventures.

â¥ Jante

For more information on Jante Ziarra's work or to just say hello, you can contact her at:Â janteziarra@gmail.com
<blockquote>"Twenty years from now you will be more disappointed by the things you didnât do than by the ones you did do. So throw off the bowlines. Sail away from the safe harbor. Catch the trade winds in your sails. Explore. Dream. Discover."</blockquote>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Impressive, most impressive.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2012/07/08/warrior/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 08 Jul 2012 21:01:15 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=23</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Last night, I was fortunate enough to see the last show of the Foster the People with special guest, Kimbra, tour. It was a sold out show at my favorite venue, The Cosmopolitan in Las Vegas! I recommend this venue to anyone who wants to see their favorite artist in an open, more intimate atmosphere. It's rooftop, poolside and overlooks the Las Vegas strip, with the Eiffel tower from the Paris hotel within plain sight.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/20120708-190515.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/20120708-190515.jpg" alt="20120708-190515.jpg" /></a>

Kimbra put on a spectacular performance! I have seen her live performances online and was impressed, but that didn't stop me from being in awe throughout her entire performance. Kimbra's vocal range combined with her classy, yet spunky attitude and how she somehow manages to mix it up with some slight booty poppin makes for a visually and auditorily pleasing performance.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/20120708-185847.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/20120708-185847.jpg" alt="20120708-185847.jpg" /></a>

Foster the People did not disappoint me either. They are easily one of the best bands I've seen live and I will continue to vouch for them. I saw them this past December at Seattle's Deck the Hall Ball so I already knew I would be in for a treat. From Mark Foster's eclectic dancing to their uptempo feel good beats, Foster the People is the band to see if you want to have an all around feel good. Whether their song be slow or fast, each song is easily danceable.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/20120708-190352.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/07/20120708-190352.jpg" alt="20120708-190352.jpg" /></a>

Kimbra joined Foster the People on stage to do "Warrior," Mark Foster got pranked by his band during their encore and ended the show in the crowd. All in all, just about each factor to this show (minus the heat) made for probably the best show I've been too. Foster the People wrapped up their tour, but Kimbra will be touring come fall and you don't want to miss it!]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Renegades.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2012/08/02/renegades/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 02 Aug 2012 06:48:28 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=32</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align:center;">I made it out to the Los Angeles, <a href="http://www.renegadecraft.com/" target="_blank">Renegade Craft Fair</a> with these goons of mine. <a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/dsc_0008-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-36" title="Renegades" alt="" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/dsc_0008-copy.jpg?w=1024" width="590" height="396" /></a> We each are into our own art, so it was definitely something worth checking out! Even if you aren't the artsy-type, it is still a good time. There were tons of talented, independent artists that create amazing art in different mediums. If I had all the money in the world, I would have walked away with something from just about every booth! You get to own something unique, that isn't mass-produced like lots of other things we may own. This fair goes on in Brooklyn, Chicago, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Austin, and London, so if possible, support the independent artists of the world! Eventually, I want to start making plushes again so it was great to see what was out there!</p>
Here are some notable ones I came across:

<a href="http://www.ohhellofriendblog.com"><img alt="" src="http://i305.photobucket.com/albums/nn206/ohhellofriend/blog%20buttons/180x75.jpg" /> </a>

<a href="http://www.etsy.com/shop/emandsprout"><img alt="" src="https://sphotos-b.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-ash3/526869_10150694714503856_704777435_n.jpg" height="150" /> </a>

<a href="http://www.lovenailtree.com/"><img alt="" src="http://media.cargocollective.com/1/3/109311/headerimg/lnt_logo-2.png" height="50" /> </a>

<a href="http://www.etsy.com/shop/Isette"><img alt="" src="http://img1.etsystatic.com/000/0/0/iusb_760x100.5914801.jpg" height="50" /> </a>

<a href="http://www.etsy.com/shop/misnopalesart"><img alt="" src="http://img3.etsystatic.com/000/0/0/iusb_760x100.9224675.jpg" height="50" /> </a>

<a href="http://theposterlist.com/"><img alt="" src="http://www.theposterlist.com/images/00118-logoImage.gif" height="50" /> </a>

<a href="http://www.etsy.com/shop/berkleyillustration/"><img alt="" src="http://img0.etsystatic.com/006/0/5215360/iusb_760x100.9979008_cpk7.jpg" height="50" /> </a>

<a href="http://mehoi.com/"><img alt="" src="http://mehoi.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/OutlineHeader.jpg" height="50" /></a>
<p style="text-align:center;">We headed to Little Tokyo afterwards. It is a nice to explore there and feel like you somehow stumbled into Japan. We ate at Orochon Ramen. It was good, but not as good as places like Shinsengumi, Ramen Yamadaya, &amp; What's Up Men in Orange County. There is also a hole in a wall bakery with taiyaki for only $1.50 and worth every cent! I can never remember the name, but it's a nice adventure trying to find it.
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/dsc_0010-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-36" title="Downtown LA" alt="" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/08/dsc_0010-copy.jpg?w=1024" width="590" height="396" /></a></p>
Create/Explore.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>In Flight.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2012/12/02/in-flight/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 02 Dec 2012 13:59:50 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=55</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[On board Singapore Airlines, on a flight from Los Angeles to Tokyo. If what the Mayans say is true and we will only make it to twenty-one days this December, I will glad I did make it to Tokyo. Japan, the country of a culture I once obsessed over all throughout high school and then some, the country that is held responsible for many of my weak spots- from food to anime! This trip is a mission and I say, "challenge accepted." However, I am not there... yet.

I do not think I have ever sat on my rear for this long consecutively. I did manage to watch four movies, currently debating on a fifth. The Dark Knight Rises is on here and I have been so tempted to watch it, but I have seen it twice and there is an abundance of movies!

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/12/photo-3.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-410 alignnone" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/12/photo-3.jpg?w=580" alt="Moonrise Kingdom" width="334" height="324" /></a>

First choice: Moonrise Kingdom. Wes Anderson does not fail. Enjoyed some Riesling while I watched that one. How perfect. It's a feel good movie with young love and great cinematography.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/12/20121202-225838.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2012/12/20121202-225838.jpg" alt="20121202-225838.jpg" /></a>
Next I watched Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter. The fights are well choreographed, however it did feel a bit slow. Dozed off on that, but to discredit it for being the cause, they did provide our meal during that time. Soba and pork katsu curry! Average, of course, but it got me stoked for what is in store for me once this plane lands.

I wanted to lighten things up after that and watched Bachelorette. Never heard of it? Me neither. But there were big names like Kirsten Dunst and James Marsden, so I gave it a whirl. Surprisingly, not bad. Kind of like Bridesmaids which they say is the female Hangover.

I saw a trailer for Seeking a Friend for the End of The World a bit ago and wanted to watch it, so I did. It was good. Along the lines of Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind, Garden State and Lost in Translation. A male with a mediocre life meets quirky girl and it goes from there. Eternal Sunshine will forever be my favorite so I hold any other movie with the same general concept to those standards. I do recommend it. The apocalypse twist makes for a interesting concept.

There will be fun posts to come. For now, I am forever on a plane.

Sayoonara.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Revival.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/03/13/revival/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 13 Mar 2013 23:02:56 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=57</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align:left;"><del></del>Finally back on here after many technical difficulties, amongst others. Â I previously posted while in flight to Tokyo; it has not beenÂ forgotten. Â Expect posts from that trip! Â Most recently, I had theÂ privilegeÂ of returning to the Pacific Northwest, more specifically, Seattle. Â I do miss it. Â After living there for four years, a week is hardly enough time for anything.</p>
<p style="text-align:left;">The Seattle Great Wheel got installed on the pier in downtown Seattle within the year I moved away. Â So of course, I had to experience it. Â It was pretty neat. Â I imagine the ride to be more beautiful on a sunny day!</p>
<p style="text-align:left;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/dsc_0008-copy.jpg"><img id="i-90" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/dsc_0008-copy.jpg?w=487" alt="Image" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align:left;">One thing I was really craving was the spicy ramen from <a href="http://www.samurainoodle.com/">Samurai Noodle</a>. Â I had a spicy tsukemen, dipping ramen, before I moved, so this time I got regular ramen. Â The Tonkotsu from Hell. Â It was so good, but trust me, you might suffer the consequence of eating something that red!</p>
<p style="text-align:left;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/tonkotsufromhell.jpg"><img id="i-96" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/tonkotsufromhell.jpg?w=487" alt="Image" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align:left;">I also took advantage of how close it is to drive up to Vancouver, B.C. Â I did not realize how big they are on FOOD!!!!!!!! Â If I had all the money in the world, I would have probably strolled down each street and eat at every food establishment I passed. Â I did stumble upon <a href="http://meatandbread.ca/">Meat &amp; Bread</a>Â while roaming the Canadian streets around Victory Square. Â I'm almost positive I've seen them on Food Network because there are not many restaurants dedicated to the simplicity of a sandwich. Â My friend and I shared the Porchetta sandwich. Â DELICIOUS! Â Aside from the food, Â I very much enjoyed the architecture and design of Â the restaurant; very clean, simple and straight to the point, just like their food. Â That was another observation I had, a lot of shops and restaurants had a very clean look, design and good typography in Vancouver.</p>
<p style="text-align:left;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/meatbread.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-116" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/meatbread.jpg?w=551" alt="meat&amp;bread" width="551" height="551" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align:left;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/dsc_0004-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-117 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/02/dsc_0004-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="DSC_0004 copy" width="474" height="318" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align:left;">I also ate at <a href="http://www.theeatery.ca/"> The Eatery</a> while in Canada, hence why I only ate half a sandwich at Meat &amp; Bread. Â I had plans to indulge in Japanese food. Â They call themselves, "the funkiest place for Japanese food," and that they are. Â From Astro Boy to creatures from 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea to Andy Warhol paintings, the atmosphere of The Eatery will not disappoint. Â The sushi was good, I had the Bob Marley, Drunken Monkey, Paper Crane, and Alaska Roll, with Bob Marley being the best, a side order of Tuna Sashimi that melts in your mouth, and a lychee mojito. Â If you're looking for the BEST quality sushi, this is not not the place, but if you're looking for good sushi with a good, hip, funÂ atmosphere, this is the place for you.</p>
<p style="text-align:left;"><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/eatery.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-124" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/03/eatery.jpg?w=551" alt="eatery" width="551" height="413" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align:left;">I highly recommend a visit to the Pacific Northwest! I wish I had more time to visit and the opportunity to drive down to Portland, Oregon as well. If you love food and the richness of culture of the city as much as I do, you will not be disappointed. The abundance of these make up for the lack of sun and warm weather.</p>]]></content:encoded>

  <title>Japon.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/05/03/japon/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 03 May 2013 19:24:58 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>

  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I suppose the only way I will actually post more is if I set smaller goals. After my trip to Japan, I decided I would go through &amp; edit ALL my photos before any is set free into the interwebz. Bad idea? Yes. After spending too much time tending to matters I thought mattered, such as finally finishing my Bachelor's Degree a million years late, but first needing to retake Math &amp; English because California requirements be hatin' on my out-of-state credits to find that either way, I am still not going to be attending in this autumn has got my mind going all. What I love is traveling, taking photos, art, food, the finer things in life. Society has built up going to college, getting your degree, but it seems like college-educated people are highly produced in this day &amp; age &amp; can often end up in the very same boat as you, despite their pursuit of "advancing" their knowledge within institutions. Me? I want to live &amp; I am still trying to figure out what that is like through the nooks &amp; crannies. Â <a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/japon13_051-copy.jpg"><img id="i-136" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/japon13_051-copy.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" /></a><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/japon13_052-copy.jpg"><img id="i-138" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/japon13_052-copy.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" /></a><a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/japon13_046-copy.jpg"><img id="i-132" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/05/japon13_046-copy.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Always NOM.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/06/08/always-nom/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 08 Jun 2013 10:18:32 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=154</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I'm the WORST at blogging. Â It's past midnight, deep into the twilight hours &amp; I've been feeling inspired today to be productive but life happens &amp; I had to get myself to work. Â It was my friends' birthday today, errr yesterday, errr even more into the past depending on the time zone. Â My friend June is a huge reason why I was finally able to take a trip to Japan, so I figured what better way to integrate more photos from that trip than by acknowledging his birthday!!! WOO. Â I hope you ate for me! Â We met when he moved to Hawai'i in the third grade &amp; now his twin brother is married to my cousin, so we are practically family! Â Happy birthday to the both of you. Â We stumbled into the Parco shops in Shibuya &amp; found this neat photo thing, complete with our bags from Uniqlo that was next door.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_218-copy.jpg"><img id="i-156" class="aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_218-copy.jpg?w=487" alt="Image" width="487" height="301" /></a>There are A LOT of shops here. Â I was super excited because there was a Vivienne Westwood shop that I could never or just haven't stumbled upon in the U.S. Â Most importantly, there is a J.S. Burgers Cafe!!! My friend, Meina, recommended it &amp; I fell in love. Â I am convinced it is my favorite burger EVER &amp; believe me, I have eaten a lot of burgers... A LOT of food, period, for that matter.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_136-copy.jpg"><img id="i-176" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_136-copy.jpg?w=487" alt="Image" /></a>

On this trip, I realized I am pretty bad at photographing my food with my Nikon because I am much more interested &amp; TOO distracted by food. Â This is the "avocado &amp; raw ham" burger which is pretty much prosciutto. Â I was mostly intrigued at the "raw ham" part when I ordered it, but I was extremely satisfied with my decision. Â I'm getting hungrier by the minute. Â Those are not sweet potato fries, although it may look that way. Â Not a fan anyway, but of course, them fries were delicious too! Not to mention their homemade sangria. Â My only complaint with the sangria is that it was soooo small! Also, they are very into heineken there for whatever reason. Â Highly recommended burger spot if you are ever in Japan. Â There are a bunch of locations throughout Tokyo. Â Very random being that I was in Japan and Japanese food is my number one, but it is sort of my favorite meal there. Â I got my friend June going there often. Â They have stamp cards!

Another favorite meal is the tsukemen from Rokurinsha. Â Luckily, we made it on a not so busy night. Â One location is in the Tokyo Sky Tree. Â There is a wait, but is well worth it.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_087-copy.jpg"><img id="i-190" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_087-copy.jpg?w=487" alt="Image" /></a>

Another not so great photo, but I was hungry! Â I had the bright idea to walk to the Tokyo Sky Tree from Minami-senshu because it was visible from there, but believe me, it was quite a walk. Â Anyway, this place specializes in the dipping style ramen. Â Whenever there is a line for food, you just hope it better be worth the wait &amp; this meal definitely hit the spot. Â We were offered bibs, which we both denied then later regretted. Â This ramen does require slurping of the noodles and the broth will splash all over you! Â The broth is of pork + fish &amp; the noodles are thick, which altogether creates a very satiating moment for your taste buds &amp; your tummy! Â Another highly recommended spot indeed! Â I may be a bit biased though considering Japan is the utopia for all my favorite food and everything else in between... but mostly FOOD! Â Japan for me is like a kid in a candy store. Â There will be more food posts.

Since I spoke of the Parco shops, I just wanted to share a neat jacket I saw for those interested in fashion. Â Seeing all the current fashion trends in America now, makes me wish I bought more clothes while I was in Japan, but being the foodie and awesome friend/relative/girlfriend that I am, I spent all my money on food and gifts. Â Japan is definitely ahead with fashion scene because a lot of the trends I saw there are making its way here now. Â But anyway, here is the jacket.Â <a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_219-copy.jpg"><img id="i-209" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/japon13_219-copy.jpg?w=487" alt="Image" /></a>

I was so intrigued by the display, &amp; the jacket was more of a sculpture to me. Â A work of art, indeed. Â MORE of Japan or here or there or anywhere to come SOON. Promise.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Keepin' it Raw!</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/06/11/keepin-it-raw/</link>
  <pubDate>Tue, 11 Jun 2013 02:14:49 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=217</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[My number one food of choice? SUSHI! Hands down. Â When I get sad + stressed, I want sushi, when I'm happy, I want sushi. I could probably eat it all day, everyday, and still be pleased. Last night I was even watching Ramsay's Best Restaurant on Netflix and told my boyfriend that I would rather eat at just a "good" Japanese restaurant than the "best" of any other because I would still be more satisfied. Too much? Haha

Growing up in Hawai'i, GOOD fish is sooooo easily accessible. I think that is one of the major parts I miss most about Hawai'i. I mean, in the states I would NEVER buy sushi at a grocery store, but you can go into a bunch in Hawai'i and get good fish.Â I also think it is pretty safe to say that you can get delicious sushi at almost any sushi joint there. Each time I move, I feel like I have to dig and do research to find a sushi spot I enjoy. Since I've moved to Orange County, my go to spot is Kaisen Kaiten Sushi in Santa Ana. It's pretty much Costa Mesa, right across of South Coast Plaza. It's a conveyor belt sushi place which "kaiten" usually represents. Sushi comes around on the belt with a specific color that symbolizes it's price. The prices are pretty good, averaging at $2, and I like getting the daily handroll deal. On Thursdays, you can get a softshell crab handroll for only $1.75. I've never had softshell crab until that deal because it's usually one of the more pricier items as far as sushi goes and the only time I get it is if I end up here on a Thursday.

I have been craving sushi (nothing new) and was trying to find a good all-you-can-eat sushi restaurant because I just really wanted to indulge THAT much on sushi. I ended up deciding that I usually eat all I can eat when I go to Kaisen, I'll have more variety (I won't have to eat entire 8-piece rolls), and it will still be cheaper.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/kaisen.jpg"><img id="i-234" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/kaisen.jpg?w=597" alt="Image" /></a>

Albacore, Hamachi, and Ahi sashimi. Plates on plates on plates! This image only shows half the stack of plates. I was waaaay too hungry to take more pictures. I left pretty content and full. Nom nom nom.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Man of Steel.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/06/21/man-of-steel/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 21 Jun 2013 03:53:12 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=260</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[It all started when...Â <a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/photo.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image" id="i-263" alt="Image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/photo.jpg?w=552" /></a>

I blame this midnight showing for this past week! Â I can't believe it was a week ago that this movie came out. Â All this time in between, I feel like, I have been half asleep due to the sleep sacrificed in order to see Superman himself. Â Never really been too big on Superman because he seemed a little too cliche, but since the Dark Knight came out last year, Superman it is! Â There are a lot of flashbacks. Â I enjoyed them a lot and feel like they were done best out of the whole movie. Â The cinematography and mood of the flashbacks were very artsy and beautifully done. Â Not to mention a bearded Henry Cavill! Â General Zod, not so much my favorite villain. Â I'll take the Joker and Bane any day! Â Amy Adams, also would not be my first choice for Lois Lane, but hey! Â I'm not the one getting the big bucks! Â The fight scenes were amazing! Â They reminded me of anime- fights were well choreographed, crisp, and swift, and I liked how the environment crumbled if Superman hit the ground or any other structure. Â I'll take all the CGI the world has to offer for those bad ass fight scenes. Â After all, he is a man of steel. Â Like I said, I have never really been a fan of Superman so I can't say much as far as his story goes. Â With the movie, I was hooked and impressed at the beginning of the movie, had some parts that turned me off, was even disappointed at the end of the movie, but at the end of the day, I would love to see this movie again. Â The good parts were great, the bad parts were okay, but it's Superman! Â The Batman series still hold my heart and the Dark Knight will continue hold my standards for other epic superhero movies until another movie takes the cake. Â So yes, SEE IT! Â I'll be seeing it again, hopefully.

Mmm... food. Â I have barely taken any pictures all week. Â That does not mean I did not eat. Â There is a local brewery in Fullerton, CA called Bootleggers. Â Wednesday nights are trivia and yesterday theÂ  <a href="http://www.garlicscapestruck.com/">Garlicscapes Food Truck</a> graced us with their presence. Â Let me just say, if you are a fan of garlic and fries and just DELICIOUS food... you need the garlic feta fries in your life. Â OH MY! $5 bucks and worth every cent!]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Turning Japanese.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/06/28/turning-japanese/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 28 Jun 2013 03:47:38 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=307</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Any given day, a sushi craving would automatically send my boyfriend and I to Kaisen Kaiten Sushi, but this time we decided to stay close and try something new. Â <a href="http://yo-ri.com/">Yori Modern Japanese Cuisine</a> just opened in Brea, CA and a couple of my friends recommended the place, giving it a stamp of approval. Â I'm always a skeptical when it comes to Japanese food, but after looking over the menu, the lunch special seemed like a good deal so we gave it a shot. Â Not to mention, I did enjoy the look of their menu and the design the restaurant. You can get a two item lunch special INCLUDING nine pieces of sashimi and one more item for only $9.50. Â Sashimi alone can typically run at that price and I was even afraid that they would charge more if you chose sashimi as one of your items. Â I was going to be adventurous with my second item, but decided to stick to my usual tempura since it was first meal at Yori. Â I usually like to test out new places with my standard food of choice or their specialty.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/image-1.jpg"><img id="i-306" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/image-1.jpg?w=607" alt="Image" /></a>

The mixed tempura was good, but there was nothing special about the tempura, the batter could have been flakier, however I do prefer their tempura dipping sauce over everywhere else. Â It was more dense in flavor and saltier than usual. Â I usually end up dipping my tempura in the wasabi/soy sauce concoction that I use for my sushi, but I didn't really need to with this one.
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/image.jpg"><img id="i-305" class="size-full wp-image" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/image.jpg?w=593" alt="Image" /></a>
The sashimi on the other hand, it was GOOD! Â For one, it was fresh and good quality. Â I was nervous because it was such a bargain. Â It's rare to have sashimi and one more item for that price and have no complaints with the fish. Â I'm curious to see if their prices will stay the same once they gain more customers. Â Their menu has a lot of items that seems like they are worth exploring. Â I recommend this place is you are looking for lower priced, more casual Japanese restaurant in North Orange County area.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Hangry. </title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/06/28/hangry/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 28 Jun 2013 04:48:30 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=363</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I have this problem where when I'm hungry, I like to watch food shows, look at pictures of food, talk about food, etcetera. Â Maybe somewhere in myÂ subconsciousÂ I feel like my appetite can be satiated through the other senses. Â Instead, I get hangry! Â But now, I will tell you about the <a href="http://burgermonster.net/">Burger Monster</a>.Â <a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/hangry1.jpg"><img id="i-362" class="aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/hangry1.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" width="650" height="578" /></a>

Just yesterday, I was discussing burgers with my friend. Â I told him, after that burger in Japan, I'm not too big on trying burger places anymore because I will probably not be as satisfied. Â I said I'd rather just get In-N-Out because it's cheap and I know it's good. Â Why bother spending 10 bucks on a burger that doesn't impress me? Â Well today, Burger Monster was at Bootleggers Brewery. Â I like to scope out whatever food truck is there. Â Today, I was also starving. Â Today, I saw HASH BROWNS in a burger. Â I didn't intend to eat here, but hot damn! Â The Attack of the Killer Potato burger won me over.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/photo-1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-330 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/06/photo-1.jpg?w=474" alt="Monster Burger" width="474" height="473" /></a>

Hash browns + BBQ sauce + garlic sriracha + lettuce + tomato + melted cheddar AND bacon!!!=Satisfaction, guaranteed! Â The burger was juicy, the bun (made daily by a local baker) was soft, it's delicious! Â My only complaint was that I didn't get fries to go with my burger. Â What was I thinking? Â I was thinking I was just sampling this burger, splitting it with the boyfriend while we enjoy half a pint of the Bootleggers Knuckle Sandwich beer, which I also recommend. Â It's a double IPA, 10 percent alcohol, and still manages to be kind to your flavor palette. Â Anyway, back to Burger Monster. Â I noticed they had many variations of fries, one of which were carnivore fries that included pastrami in the mix. Â So yes, lesson of the day, always get fries with your burger! Â And eat at Burger Monster.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Man Can Create Beauty. </title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/07/03/man-can-create-beauty/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 03 Jul 2013 10:22:51 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=380</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_161-copy.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-386 aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_161-copy.jpg" alt="Sky Tree Asakusa" width="580" height="389" /></a>

Sometimes things are farther than they are appear to be, but it doesn't mean it's not within your reach.

<img id="i-379" class="size-full wp-image aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_085-copy.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" />

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_080-copy.jpg"><img id="i-378" class="size-full wp-image aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_080-copy.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" /></a>

Because I could see the Tokyo Sky Tree from our hotel in Asakusa, I decided that it was definitely walking distance (which isn't really the best conclusion when it's the tallest building in Japan). Â I can't even remember how long the walk was. Â I can only remember the journey: Debating whether or not to hop in a taxi, finding a path across the river, a man shooting photos against the nightscape backdrop, a man walking two pugs, and theÂ exhilaration of the bright structures of the night and the satisfaction of finally reaching your destination, especially through a cityÂ Â you've never been to. Â Had I taken the easiest route from point A to B, I would have never experienced the little things that made destination even more worthwhile.

The view of the Sky Tree itself is a beauty, but once you get in it, you can experience a 360 view of Tokyo, including the Tokyo Tower. Â If you are a fan of vinegar, there is a delicious vinegary drink in the tower itself. Â There are a bunch of shops and restaurants here including the tsukemen place, <a href="http://www.rokurinsha.com/">Rokurinsha</a>, I previously wrote about. Â There is also a matcha (green tea) place with really good ice cream!

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_101-copy.jpg"><img id="i-382" class="size-full wp-image aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/japon13_101-copy.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" /></a>

Although I do not recommend the walk to everyone, I do recommend exploring Asakusa on a visit to Tokyo, especially if you want a bit of a homely vibe on your Â trip. Â There is a train that can get you right to and from the Sky Tree. Â Asakusa broughtÂ the illustrations of anime to life and it was also nice to see a sense of community with the obaachans (grandmas) and ojiichans (grandpas) walking and biking around, or just hanging out, and seeing smaller speciality shops opposed to franchised corporations. Â It's just a nice place to get away from the hustle and bustle of the city, but still be right there!]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Salty Air, Chicken &amp; Waffles.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/07/26/salty-air-chicken-waffles/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 26 Jul 2013 02:54:48 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=393</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Had to drop a friend off in the early morning hours at the Long Beach Airport. It was so early that <a href="http://www.roscoeschickenandwaffles.com/">Roscoe's House of Chicken and Waffles</a> wasn't even open yet, so I decided to kill some time by heading to Redondo Beach. When I moved to California, I thought I would finally be able to be at the beach often. Unfortunately, that hasn't the case. Therefore, the infrequent visits make the rarity of the salty ocean air that much more satisfying. I also thought that it would be a great idea to drive on the Pacific Coast Highway from Long Beach to Redondo Beach, but it is really one of most unsatisfying parts I've seen of the PCH yet. Either way, it was a beautiful morning spent with the boy at the beach.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/fries.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-394 size-full" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/fries.jpg" alt="Bradley" width="3872" height="2592" /></a>

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/redondo.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-395 size-full" title="Redondo Beach" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/redondo.jpg" alt="" width="3620" height="2585" /></a>

Especially when followed by chicken &amp; waffles for breakfast! If you've been to or live in Southern California, you know Roscoe's! Chicken AND waffles, 'nuff said. If you live in California, you've been here or you're missing out and if you are going to visit California, you need to eat here! Â There are a few locations throughout LA County and one in the works in Anaheim. Â The boyfriend is born &amp; raised in California, yet NEVER had Roscoe's so you know I had to take care of that. Â He was pleased. Â What more can I say? Â Eat at Roscoe's.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/photo-2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-397 size-full" title="Roscoe's Chicken &amp; Waffles" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/07/photo-2.jpg" alt="" width="611" height="611" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Kniight Riider</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/08/11/kniight-riider/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 11 Aug 2013 18:19:59 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=419</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Knight Rider? No, not the popular TV show of the 80s featuring David Hasselholf! Forget every association with David Hasselhoff and this image:
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kitt-from-knight-rider-7.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-423 alignnone" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kitt-from-knight-rider-7.jpg" alt="Knight Rider" width="400" height="300" /></a>

And remember this one:
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kniightriider.jpg"><img id="i-420" class=" wp-image alignnone" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kniightriider.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" width="585" height="392" /></a>
Kniight Riider is now your new favorite song done by <a href="https://soundcloud.com/joeymireles">Joey Mireles</a>!

<a href="https://soundcloud.com/joeymireles"><img class="size-large wp-image-424 alignnone" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kr.jpg?w=590" alt="https://soundcloud.com/joeymireles" width="590" height="440" /></a>

Joey recently asked me to shoot a photo for his album art. Â Yes, David Hasselhoff ran through my mind when I was told the song title, but with "Knight" involved, I immediately thought of the Dark Knight. Â Hence, the Batman inspired photo. Â It's a feel good, dance-your-ass-off kinda track so I highly recommend you check it out atÂ <a href="https://soundcloud.com/joeymireles">https://soundcloud.com/joeymireles</a>Â !

But if is how you feel

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/fuud.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-430" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/fuud.jpg?w=590" alt="FOOD" width="590" height="590" /></a>

Food I shall bring! Â I have been way too involved in eating my food, rather than sharing what I'm eating (go figure). Â I mentioned the <a href="https://twitter.com/garlicscape">GarlicScapes Food Truck</a> a few posts back, but no pictures. Â I like to measure how good food is not only by the satisfaction of the initial flavors from when the food hits Â your taste buds, but also by how badly you crave it afterwards. For a good week or two after eating the garlic feta fries, my best friend and I kept wanting it back in our lives. Â If you love garlic + feta + fries, this is it!

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-432" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes2.jpg?w=590" alt="Garlic Feta Fries" width="590" height="590" /></a>

The fries alone are $5, but they also offer a slider combo for $10.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-434" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes1.jpg?w=590" alt="Slider Combo" width="590" height="590" /></a>

The sliders are good, but not their strongest point. Â I heard their grilled cheese is delicious, but I haven't been able to try it yet. Â It's on my list! I am definitely still in love with those fries though.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-433" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes.jpg?w=590" alt="GarlicScapes Food Truck" width="590" height="590" /></a>

&nbsp;

You can find the GarlicScapes Food Truck in the Orange County area. Â It seems their website is still under construction, so here is a link to their twitter <a href="https://twitter.com/garlicscape">GarlicScapes Food Truck </a>. So now you can go on a drive to get some garlic feta fries while listening to Kniight Riider!]]></content:encoded>

  <title>Mind Blown.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/09/20/mind-blown/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 20 Sep 2013 05:49:07 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=443</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I have been extremely M.I.A., as usual, with blogging, but I never realized I could have the perfect birthday cake until now. Behold, the Sushi Cake:

<img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/enhanced/webdr03/2013/9/19/19/enhanced-buzz-27149-1379632299-10.jpg">

Found on Buzzfeed's <p><a href='http://www.buzzfeed.com/leonoraepstein/food-mashups-thatll-blow-your-mind'>18 Food Mashups That&#039;ll Blow Your Mind</a>.</p>

Alongside, the Spaghetti Bread:
<img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/enhanced/webdr06/2013/9/19/18/enhanced-buzz-13883-1379629134-14.jpg">

and the Ramen Crust Pizza?
<img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/enhanced/webdr06/2013/9/19/19/enhanced-buzz-25640-1379634947-9.jpg">

Obviously, I'm more interested in savory versus sweets. However there is a pumpkin pie in a cupcake that has got me intrigued.  Buzzfeed was also nice enough to include recipes alongside these food fusions for you to make in the comfort of your own home.
]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>French Soul Food.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/10/10/french-soul-food/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 10 Oct 2013 20:44:42 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=448</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[With the destination set to San Francisco, "What food shall I eat?" was the top priority on my mind. My sister threw out a place she saw on Food Network that had beignets, <a href="http://frenchsoulfood.com/home/#/i/0">Brenda's French Soul Food</a>. Â I immediately googled this restaurant and with 4 stars and over 4000 reviews on Yelp, I figured it must be good! My family and I decided to go there for brunch on a Sunday morning. We walked up the street trying to find the place, when suddenly, a crowd appeared. This must be the place. The wait ended up being 45 minutes to an hour. We don't always wait thaaaat long for food, but when we do, it's because we're on vacation. Â Another factor was that I read waaay too much on their beignets and my sister and I were dying to try it. We've never had beignets before and this place had us sold with the flight of beignets they offered: Plain, Ghiradelli Chocolate, Granny Smith Apple, and Crawfish. Our party was finally called to be seated! Jackpot. WE GET TO EAAAAT! I started off with the Guava Mimosa, while my family ordered the Watermelon iced tea. We are impressed. Next came our flight of beignets:

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/beignets.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-449" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/beignets.jpg" alt="Beignet Flight" width="590" height="210" /></a>

All delicious! Â I am typically a savory, over sweet kind-of-gal, but surprisingly, I really liked the Ghiradelli Chocolate one. Â The melted chocolate was perfectly balanced in flavor within the beignet.

Alas, brunch is served!

Hangtown Fry: Â Crispy oyster, bacon &amp; scallion scramble,Â with hash + cream biscuit

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/hangtownfry.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-451" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/hangtownfry.jpg?w=590" alt="Hangtown Fry" width="590" height="590" /></a>

French Toast: Cinnamon-battered brioche +Â butter pecan sauce

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/frenchtoast.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-452" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/frenchtoast.jpg?w=590" alt="French Toast" width="590" height="590" /></a>

Pulled Pork Eggs Benedict:Â Two poached eggs and pulled pork on cream biscuits withÂ creole hollandaise + Â grits

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/pulledporkbenedict.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-454" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/pulledporkbenedict.jpg?w=590" alt="Pulled Pork Benedict" width="590" height="590" /></a>

Foster's Banana French Toast with butter rum sauce

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/fostersfrenchtoast.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-453" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/10/fostersfrenchtoast.jpg?w=590" alt="Foster's French Toast" width="590" height="590" /></a>

(Excuse the blurry photo, I was starving by then)

Soo good! Â Unless you have a huge sweet tooth, I recommend getting the Banana Foster's French Toast if they're offering it because the French Toast is more of a dessert. Everything was delicious down to the biscuits that accompanied my Hangtown Fry. We were all pleased with our food.

They do offer meals all day with dinner including gumbo, fried chicken, catfish, and ribs. I really wish I could have indulged in dinner there because they even have hushpuppies, which I love but rarely come across given I don't live in the south. If you live in the Bay area or plan on making a trip there, do yourself a favor and have a feast at <a href="http://frenchsoulfood.com/home/#/i/0">Brenda's French Soul Food</a>.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Travel Through Food</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/10/31/travel-through-food/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 31 Oct 2013 03:08:28 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=467</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/2013-10/enhanced/webdr02/21/16/anigif_enhanced-buzz-31920-1382387945-2.gif" alt="" />

Sometimes I wish I could have the wardrobe of others, but then I realize that I EAT all my money away. The perfect flavors upon my palette bring on a better experience for me to enjoy than the perfect outfit. Maybe if I was frugal enough with my eating habits too, I would have been able to go on another trip by now, only to spend my trip in an awesome place eating anything and everything. Then I realized, when you explore different restaurants and food trucks and anything in between, it's as if you're on a mini vacation for that time being.

I live in a state where each food establishment is diverse enough and have their own way of things, their specialties, and when you step foot into that atmosphere, you experience a different culture. In these past few weeks, I've been to an Indian restaurant, a Mexican-French cafe, Shabu Shabu, sushi coming around on a conveyor belt, from Korean barbecue to a vegan food truck, a Mexican-Korean food truck, an Italian restaurant specializing in wood fired pizza and a whole lot of in-between. Each bring their own uniqueness, something of their own.

If you can't afford to travel the world, travel through food. Explore places that are offered to you around your home. After all, aside from physically exploring the views of somewhere new in the world, exploring through food is also top priority. You get to experience the culture better and get a taste firsthand (pun intended). If you're in Hawaii, your trip isn't complete without poke or musubi and if you're in California, you will initially head to In-N-Out, salmon in Washington, crab cakes in Maryland, French fries in France... just kidding! But yes, if you did otherwise, your trip would be left incomplete.

Explore the world through food.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Because Hors d'oeuvre</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/10/24/because-hors-doeuvre/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 24 Oct 2013 04:42:18 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=474</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Currently on <a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/">Buzzfeed</a>Â (my biggest distraction, besides eating):

<a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/arianelange/its-pretty-clear-you-are-obsessed-with-food">22 Moments When It's Pretty Clear You Are Obsessed With Food</a>.
<h2 style="margin:0;padding:0 0 8px;border:0;outline:0;font-size:26px;background-color:#ffffff;line-height:28px;font-family:ProximaNovaSemibold, Helvetica, Arial;font-weight:normal;color:#121212;"><span class="buzz_superlist_number_inline" style="margin:0;padding:0;border:0;outline:0;font-size:25.555555343628px;background-color:transparent;display:inline;background-position:initial initial;background-repeat:initial initial;">6.</span>Â When people warn you that youâll âspoil your appetite,â you can see right through that nonsense.</h2>
<img alt="" src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/2013-10/enhanced/webdr02/23/13/anigif_enhanced-buzz-25306-1382550615-9.gif" />

Because anything eaten before your meal is just the first course, right?

or

14. At dinner when people tell you you have food on your face, and itâs like, âOf course, I am eating.â

Because at that moment, there also happens to be food in my teeth too. So what?

18. You realize your dreams are a bitâ¦different from other peopleâs.

Like that one time my dream revolved around red velvet cheesecake or a giant mochi ball you had to hold with two hands or a dream of eating the finest sushi in Japan... that I happened to have just the other night!

Because
19. Itâs the simple things that make you happy

Pure happiness!]]></content:encoded>

  <title>Me, Hungry.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/04/me-hungry/</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 04 Nov 2013 17:57:41 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>

  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/erinchack/signs-being-hungry-is-your-primary-emotion">21 Signs Being Hungry Is Your Primary Emotion</a>

<a href="http://www.buzzfeed.com/">Buzzfeed</a> knows me so well when it comes to food! Because as I am trying to type this post, I'm too distracted by thinking what it is I'm going to eat for breakfast.
<h2>4.Â When you wake up your first thought isnât,Â <i>What does this beautiful day have in store for me?</i>Â Itâs,<i>Whatâs for breakfast?</i></h2>

And I've definitely found myself thinking what life would be like if we could marry food
<h2>15.Â Youâve considering lobbying for legalized food marriage.</h2>
<img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/2013-10/enhanced/webdr03/28/14/anigif_enhanced-buzz-3377-1382985795-23.gif" width="500" height="231" />

And I'm always doing stuff like this:
<h2>18.Â You do bad things for your hunger, like eating in bed.</h2>
<img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/2013-10/enhanced/webdr01/28/13/enhanced-buzz-19449-1382983181-14.jpg" width="500" height="379" />

Which I will most likely be doing once I make breakfast!

And I'm always saying I cannot afford my hunger because I am
<div>Â <img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://s3-ec.buzzfed.com/static/2013-10/enhanced/webdr05/28/14/anigif_enhanced-buzz-26823-1382985824-4.gif" width="500" height="351" /></div>

<item>
  <title>Consumerism.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/13/consumerism/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 13 Nov 2013 22:05:08 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=529</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[One thing's for sure, I love food, but I do not agree with the mass production that is ever-so-present in our food industry. &nbsp;Although I haven't been able to go back onto the <a href="http://vegetarian.about.com/od/glossary/g/Pescatarian.htm">pescatarian</a> diet I once lived (I fell completely off that boat on a trip to the east coast; In Philly, I needed to do the <a href="http://www.genosteaks.com/">Geno's </a>versus <a href="http://www.patskingofsteaks.com/">Pat's</a> Philly Cheesesteak challenge or eat a hot dog at <a href="http://www.yelp.com/biz/grays-papaya-new-york-4">Gray's Papaya</a> in New York like they did in <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0981227/">Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist</a>), I'd prefer if animals were not treated like they are not living, breathing, creatures of this world.

A clip from the movie&nbsp;<a href="http://www.barakasamsara.com/">SAMSARA</a>&nbsp;gives us an inside look at the process of industrialized food production. &nbsp;It is shot beautifully, yet is disturbing.

http://vimeo.com/73234721

I think this is the disconnect we no longer deal with that allows for us, as Americans, to partake in this indulgence with no conscience. I went through a phase when Costco would disgust me. &nbsp;I would take a look around at all the packaged meats readily available in the masses for the simple convenience of our own consumption. &nbsp;I wondered how much of this meat would actually be consumed, how much didn't, how many animals died for nothing, and how many animals died inhumanely just for the sake of us being able to walk into a store and have the option to buy any meat, at anytime, at any store at our convenience. &nbsp;I'm trying hard to not use the word convenience so frequently, but it's hard not to when it is just that. &nbsp;The accessibility of products made for us in the masses is our country, capitalism. &nbsp;Our country thrives off of how convenient things are available for our consumption at the compromise of our health and the fair treatment of ourselves and animals. &nbsp;As long as we keep consuming and they keep seeing profits, the vicious cycle will continue.

SAMSARA, however, is not a documentary on the food industry.  It captures twenty-five countries over the course of almost five years.

From SAMSARA producer Mark Magidson: 
"We are happy this clip has struck a chord with so many people, and we hope that the interest in this clip will lead viewers to see SAMSARA in its entirety. This clip represents only 6 minutes from a 100 minute long film, which was photographed in 25 countries and explores many other diverse aspects of the human experience. We would love for viewers to experience SAMSARA as a whole."]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Cronut, Beachside</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/17/cronut-beachside/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 17 Nov 2013 18:56:51 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=540</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I made a rare, Saturday morning drive to Huntington Beach. Â Clouds hovered over my apartment, but the closer we got to the beach, the brighter the sun shone through. I was craving a bagel sandwich from <a href="http://www.yelp.com/biz/the-donuttery-huntington-beach">The Donuttery</a>;Â my heart was set on a lox bagel. Â I decided I wanted to enjoy my food on the beach, but with already a half an hour drive to The Donuttery, I needed to eat there. Â The small shop was filled with a line to the door, which was almost a relief because I thought that line would give me time to decide on a donut. Â Before you knew it, I was at the front of the line. Â I immediately knew I wanted the Goldie Lox bagel smoked salmon, tomato, red onion, cream cheese, capers and lemon pepper, but the choice of donuts were vast, I couldn't decide what direction to go with donuts ranging from pumpkin, red velvet, maple bacon bar, and wait, a <a href="http://dominiqueansel.com/cronut-101/">cronut</a>?

The cronut, the item that was continuously in the food press this year after debuting in New York City. Â The cronut, the union of a croissant and donut. Â It wasn't the original, but I had to try it. Â I opted for the glazed cronut. Â I decided to save it for the beach to enjoy with coffee and the calming backdrop, as I immediately devoured my bagel. Â Satisfaction.

I arrived at the beach, anxious to try this newfound pastry. Â The outside of the cronut was crusted in a sugary glaze, like a donut, while the inside was flaky and could be pulled apart in layers, traits of the croissant. Â I'll usually choose a croissant over a donut to avoid such a sweet indulgence, so the croissant characteristics brought to the donut created a perfect balance. Â Not to mention the joy in now being able to peel apart a donut.

I took in the beautiful scenery as I alternated between sipping my coffee and eating my cronut. It's these rare moments that make me completely appreciate living in southern California. Â A morning spent with good eats, fresh ocean air, perfect weather and my boy to share the experience with.

<img id="i-539" class=" wp-image" style="font-style:normal;" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/11/cronut.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" width="585" height="585" />Â  Â <img id="i-541" class=" wp-image" style="font-style:normal;" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/11/goldielox.jpg?w=650" alt="Image" width="585" height="585" />
<h6 class="zemanta-related-title" style="font-size:1em;">Related articles</h6>
<ul class="zemanta-article-ul">
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://adventuresofadietitian.com/2013/11/13/what-is-a-cronut/" target="_blank">What is a cronut?</a> (adventuresofadietitian.com)</li>
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://awesomemomentsofmylife.wordpress.com/2013/11/08/nuts-over-cronuts/" target="_blank">Nuts over Cronuts</a> (awesomemomentsofmylife.wordpress.com)</li>
</ul>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>"I will always be an adventurer"</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/18/iwillalwaysbeanadventurer/</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 18 Nov 2013 22:24:44 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=591</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Read the articleÂ <a href="http://convergemagazine.com/travel-young-5278/">Why You Should Travel Young</a>. Â It's written well and inspiring! I got hooked when <a href="http://goinswriter.com/">Jeff Goins</a> wrote:
<blockquote>One of the young women brought up a question.

âDo you think I should go to graduate school or move to Africa?â

I donât think she was talking to me. In fact, Iâm pretty sure she wasnât. But that didnât stop me from offering my opinion.

<a href="http://convergemagazine.com/20s-6323/">I told her to travel</a>. Hands down. No excuses. Just go.

She sighed, nodding. âYeah, butâ¦â</blockquote>
<blockquote>I had heard this excuse before, and I didnât buy it. I knew the âyeah-butâ intimately. I had uttered it many times before. The words seem innocuous enough, but are actually quite fatal."</blockquote>
Travel. Â That's always my answer. Â If you have the opportunity to live somewhere new, live it. Â I'm always an avid supporter of traveling. Â I have a friend who is in his last year of college. Â He always mentions how he wants to move out of his parents' home, ideally by the end of the year, but he also wants to take a trip when he graduates. Â I told him to take the trip, move after. Â The experience of exploring and being somewhere new would be far greater than still going through the same routines, just not being at your parents' house. Â I told him to take advantage of the fact that he won't have rent to pay from now until that time so that he could save funds for the trip and funds to move out after. Â Also by that time, once school is done, home could be anywhere!
<blockquote>While youâre young, you should travel. You should take the time to see the world and taste the fullness of life. Spend an afternoon sitting in front of the Michelangelo. Walk the streets of Paris. Climb Kilimanjaro. Hike the Appalachian trail. See the Great Wall of China. Get your heart-broken by the âkilling fieldsâ of Cambodia. Swim through the Great Barrier Reef. These are the moments that define the rest of your life; theyâre the experiences that stick with you forever.</blockquote>
A couple of years ago, I took a break from school so I could put some money towards traveling rather than tuition. Â I get upset with how life works, how unexpected obstacles can often leave you with unfulfilled daydreams. Â Sometimes with unfortunate events, you don't always have "later." Â For those who have seen the Disney Pixar movieÂ <a href="http://movies.disney.com/up">Up</a>, the opening scene broke my heart. Â Although most us will live well into old age, the thought of not being able to see parts of the world I want to see did not sit well with me so I took that trip to Iceland a few years ago. Â Then last year, I was fortunate enough to go to Japan. Â The top two countries on my list. Â I am now behind with school and often get frustrated with that fact, but I take comfort in the fact that despite everything, I was able to explore the places that I yearned to go.
<h6 class="zemanta-related-title" style="font-size:1em;">Related articles</h6>
<ul class="zemanta-article-ul">
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://generationhopeblog.wordpress.com/2013/10/30/why-young-people-need-to-travel/" target="_blank">Why Young People Need to Travel</a> (generationhopeblog.wordpress.com)</li>
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="https://medium.com/architecting-a-life/215fd34c606d">Things I learned wandering around Europe for 7 months</a></li>
</ul>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>The Great Buddha</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/18/the-great-buddha/</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 18 Nov 2013 22:54:27 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=601</guid>
  <description/>

Â It was so spiritual and so serene to be in the presence of a daibutsu, this large of a scale. Â It was an unexpected, yet truly memorable part of my trip. Â Kamakura itself is also a nice getaway from the hustle and bustle of Tokyo's city life.

<item>
  <title>Inspired by Iceland</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/20/inspired-by-iceland/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 20 Nov 2013 06:53:13 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=620</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Iceland is the one place I visited where I absolutely did not want to go home. Â I feel like on almost every trip you're on, at some point you look forward to going home. Â I think I can say that it is the one place I wasn't ready to leave when my trip was coming to the end. Â I wanted to stay. Â I sat in a bar in Reykjavik, the scent of waffles in the air, completely dreading going home the next day. Â Scent of waffles in a bar? Â That's the quirkiness of Iceland. Â A group of people, I assumed were a band because they looked like they were working on music on their MacBook, had a waffle maker at their table.

You can learn a bit about Iceland and even plan your trip onÂ <a style="font-size:13px;line-height:19px;" href="http://www.inspiredbyiceland.com/">Inspired by Iceland</a>!

</ul>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Movies That Inspire Travel</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/21/movies-that-inspire-travel/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 21 Nov 2013 09:15:58 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=650</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I came acrossÂ <a href="http://matadornetwork.com/bnt/23-movies-that-will-make-you-want-to-travel/">23 movies that will make you want to travel</a>Â on <a href="http://matadornetwork.com/">Matador Network</a>. Â It included some of my favorite movies:Â <a class="zem_slink" title="Amelie" href="http://www.amazon.com/Amelie-Audrey-Tautou/dp/B0000640VO%3FSubscriptionId%3D0G81C5DAZ03ZR9WH9X82%26tag%3Dzemanta-20%26linkCode%3Dxm2%26camp%3D2025%26creative%3D165953%26creativeASIN%3DB0000640VO" target="_blank" rel="amazon">AmÃ©lie</a>,Â <a class="zem_slink" title="Lost in Translation" href="http://www.amazon.com/Lost-Translation-Bill-Murray/dp/B00005JMJ4%3FSubscriptionId%3D0G81C5DAZ03ZR9WH9X82%26tag%3Dzemanta-20%26linkCode%3Dxm2%26camp%3D2025%26creative%3D165953%26creativeASIN%3DB00005JMJ4" target="_blank" rel="amazon">Lost in Translation</a>,Â <a class="zem_slink" title="The Darjeeling Limited" href="http://www.amazon.com/Darjeeling-Limited-Owen-Wilson/dp/B0010X8NF0%3FSubscriptionId%3D0G81C5DAZ03ZR9WH9X82%26tag%3Dzemanta-20%26linkCode%3Dxm2%26camp%3D2025%26creative%3D165953%26creativeASIN%3DB0010X8NF0" target="_blank" rel="amazon">The Darjeeling Limited</a>, and <a class="zem_slink" title="Into the Wild" href="http://www.amazon.com/Into-Wild-Emile-Hirsch/dp/B000ZN802W%3FSubscriptionId%3D0G81C5DAZ03ZR9WH9X82%26tag%3Dzemanta-20%26linkCode%3Dxm2%26camp%3D2025%26creative%3D165953%26creativeASIN%3DB000ZN802W" target="_blank" rel="amazon">Into the Wild</a>. Â Out of that list,Â <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0758758/">Into the Wild</a> was the movie that influenced me most to travel, at least throughout <a class="zem_slink" title="United States" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=38.8833333333,-77.0166666667&amp;spn=10.0,10.0&amp;q=38.8833333333,-77.0166666667 (United%20States)&amp;t=h" target="_blank" rel="geolocation">America</a>. Â It was a movie that also strongly emphasized gender barriers. Â As a woman, I would not be able to <a class="zem_slink" title="Hitchhiking" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitchhiking" target="_blank" rel="wikipedia">hitchhike</a> my way through America the way he did and make it as far as he did. Â Nonetheless, on one trip, I drove from <a class="zem_slink" title="Washington (state)" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=47.5,-120.5&amp;spn=3.0,3.0&amp;q=47.5,-120.5 (Washington%20%28state%29)&amp;t=h" target="_blank" rel="geolocation">Washington</a> to <a class="zem_slink" title="California" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=37.0,-120.0&amp;spn=10.0,10.0&amp;q=37.0,-120.0 (California)&amp;t=h" target="_blank" rel="geolocation">California</a> and eventually found myself pitching a tent in <a href="http://www.nps.gov/zion/index.htm">Zion National Park</a>Â enjoying the mountainous landscapes by myself. Â There's a sense of accomplishment in doing things alone, but the moral of the story for Into the Wild results in,

"Happiness is only real when shared."- Chris McCandless

<img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://www.masculinity-movies.com/wp-content/gallery/into-the-wild/photo_04_hires.jpg" width="700" height="405" />

<a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0335266/">Lost in Translation</a>Â is an easy inspiration for me. Â It's set in Japan! Â This movie allows you to explore Japan, culture shock and all, as these characters attempt to find themselves while being in a foreign city.

<img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://filmphilosophy.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/lost1.png" width="853" height="457" />

One movie that was not on the list, that I feel should, isÂ <a href="http://www.sonyclassics.com/midnightinparis/">Midnight in Paris</a>. Â Not only will it make you want to walk the streets of Paris in the rain, but also make you wish you could travel back in time. Â For those who daydream about traveling to Paris, especially during the Roaring Twenties, this is for you.

<img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://citizenscreenings.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/midnight-in-paris1.png?w=545&amp;h=333" width="545" height="334" />

Then there's one that isn't a movie, but a documentary, <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1094594/">Heima</a>. Â The band <a href="http://www.sigur-ros.co.uk/">Sigur Ros</a> plays free, unannounced concerts throughout Iceland, revealing its mesmerizing landscapes throughout the country. Â Watch it for beautiful music and a tour of Iceland.

<img class="alignnone" alt="" src="http://sigurros.s3.amazonaws.com/site_images/heima/extras4.jpg" width="1014" height="571" />
<h4>What movies have you made you want to travel?</h4>]]></content:encoded>

  <title>Meanwhile, in Tokyo...</title>

  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/11/neko-en.jpg" alt="Meanwhile, in Tokyo..." width="933" height="1390" />

<a class="zem_slink" title="Cat cafÃ©" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cat_caf%C3%A9" target="_blank" rel="wikipedia">Cat Cafe</a>,Â <a href="http://asakusanekoen.com/index_english.html">Asakusa Neko-en</a>,Â in the <a class="zem_slink" title="Asakusa" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=35.71472,139.79673&amp;spn=1.0,1.0&amp;q=35.71472,139.79673 (Asakusa)&amp;t=h" target="_blank" rel="geolocation">Asakusa</a> district in <a class="zem_slink" title="Tokyo" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=35.6895055556,139.6917&amp;spn=1.0,1.0&amp;q=35.6895055556,139.6917 (Tokyo)&amp;t=h" target="_blank" rel="geolocation">Tokyo, Japan</a>. Â The woman who owns this place is a sweetheart and makes me you feel at home. Â There are also a couple of ramen shops on the same street. Â Not to mention the excellent view of the <a class="zem_slink" title="Tokyo Skytree" href="http://maps.google.com/maps?ll=35.7101388889,139.810833333&amp;spn=0.01,0.01&amp;q=35.7101388889,139.810833333 (Tokyo%20Skytree)&amp;t=h" target="_blank" rel="geolocation">Tokyo Sky Tree</a>.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Fries on Fries!</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/11/30/friesonfries/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 30 Nov 2013 07:38:19 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=665</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[http://youtu.be/USbLFoxcPiA

Despite the massive amounts of delicious food at Thanksgiving, I'll always love me some fries.

<a href="http://shop.hipsandhair.com/products">Hips and Hair</a> just released a new collection and I've dying to get their <a href="http://shop.hipsandhair.com/product/death-fries-crew-tee">Death Fries</a> tee!

<a href="http://shop.hipsandhair.com/product/death-fries-crew-tee"><img alt="" src="http://images.cdn.bigcartel.com/bigcartel/product_images/128002569/max_h-1000+max_w-1000/deathfries.jpg" width="630" height="648" /></a>

The rest of their line is just as admirable too!
<a href="http://shop.hipsandhair.com/"><img class="alignnone" alt="" src="https://scontent-a-lax.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-prn2/1374908_865617385671_841770591_n.jpg" width="640" height="640" /></a>

Check them out at&nbsp;<a href="http://shop.hipsandhair.com/">shop.hipsandhair.com</a>&nbsp;!
