<item>
  <title>Maybe It's Cold Outside</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2013/12/02/maybe-its-cold-outside/</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 02 Dec 2013 08:14:38 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=680</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f1XSn8tErLs

An unexpected duet between Lady Gaga and Joseph Gordon-Levitt. I'm in love with this take on, "Baby, It's Cold Outside." The switching of gender roles was nicely done.

In California, "cold outside" will most likely be the somewhere in the 60s and what better way to warm up than with RAMEN!
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/shinsengumi.jpg"><img class="wp-image-681 aligncenter" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/shinsengumi.jpg?w=800" alt="Hakata Ramen" width="640" height="511" /></a>

At 1906 reviews on <a href="http://www.yelp.com/biz/shin-sen-gumi-hakata-ramen-fountain-valley?nb=1#query:ramen">Yelp</a>,Â <a href="http://www.shinsengumigroup.com/">Shin-Sen-Gumi Hakata Ramen</a>Â is the most reviewed restaurant for ramen in Orange County. Â Since <a href="http://www.whatsupmenus.com/menu.html">What's Up Men</a>Â opened in Fullerton, it's enough to satisfy my cravings without the drive. Â However, there are perks to the drive when it comes to Shin-Sen-Gumi. You can choose a half-size ramen, but why would you? How firm you want your noodles, how you want your broth, and specify what toppings you want in your ramen. Â If you like spicy, opt for spicy miso in your broth. Â It makes a great broth even better! Â I've never ordered the noodles firm until yesterday, but I found I like them better. Â I enjoyed them so much, I even ordered a second helping of noodles, another first for me. Â I felt like I looked like a pig when my cousin-in-law denied the offer of more noodles. Â Even after the second round of noodles, a part of me still wanted more, but I could barely move. Â I also recommend the takoyaki, but make sure you get there after 6 p.m. because appetizers are only offered for dinner.

I was excited I made the drive. Â I forgot how good the ramen is at Shin-Sen-Gumi. Â Having a guest in town usually gives me the added boost for driving further distances than usual in California. Â Traffic is real here.

Other ramen places I recommend in Orange County are:

<a href="http://www.whatsupmenus.com/menu.html">What's Up Men</a>

<a href="http://www.japaneserestaurantinfo.com/santoka/">Santouka Ramen</a>

<a href="http://www.ramen-yamadaya.com/location.html">Ramen Yamadaya</a>

Now quit reading this and get yourself a delicious bowl of ramen!
<h6 class="zemanta-related-title" style="font-size:1em;">Related articles</h6>
<ul class="zemanta-article-ul">
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://www.gossipcop.com/lady-gaga-joseph-gordon-levitt-baby-its-cold-outside-video-duet-holiday-spectacular-thanksgiving-special/" target="_blank">Lady Gaga and Joseph Gordon-Levitt Perform "Baby It's Cold Outside" on Thanksgiving Special (VIDEO)</a> (gossipcop.com)</li>
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://ramenrun.com/2013/11/19/hipster-ramen/" target="_blank">Hipster Ramen</a> (ramenrun.com)</li>
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://ramenrun.com/2013/10/25/overdue-ramen-quarterly-report/" target="_blank">Overdue Ramen Quarterly Report</a> (ramenrun.com)</li>
	<li class="zemanta-article-ul-li"><a href="http://nommingtheworld.wordpress.com/2013/10/26/shin-sen-gumi/" target="_blank">Shin Sen Gumi</a> (nommingtheworld.wordpress.com)</li>

<item>
  <title>Food Truck Fries | OC</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/02/13/foodtruckfriesoc/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 13 Feb 2014 18:13:46 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=695</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[First post of the year! What better way to start than with an ode to my favorite, FRENCH FRIES!!! (Or freedom fries for whoever thought that could actually be a thing)

My last run with fries in 2013 was withÂ a newer food truck calledÂ <a href="http://www.porkoricobbq.com/">Porko Rico</a>, the same creators ofÂ <a href="http://www.thevikingtruck.com/home">The Viking Truck</a>.

Behold theÂ Captain Porko Fries:

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/photo-copy-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-701" title="Captain Porko Fries" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/12/photo-copy-2.jpg?w=800" alt="" width="648" height="488" /></a>

"Classic crispy french fries with pulled pork, mango coleslaw, pineapple baked beans, and citrus bbq sauce"

My only complaint was that I needed more fries to balance out the the pork/slaw/beans concoction to fries ratio because it was the selling point (for me). Â I'm looking forward to trying more dishes from this food truck like the Shipwreck Grilled Cheese and Tostones.

I also ran into the <a href="http://californiagrilltruck.com/">California Grill Truck </a>while enjoying a pint of Knuckle Sandwich at <a href="http://www.bootleggersbrewery.com/">Bootlegger's Brewery</a>Â and indulged in their version of

Bulkogi Fries:

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/photo.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-705" title="Bulkogi Fries" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/photo.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="640" /></a>

"Warm fries doused with gooey melted cheese and topped with bulkogi"   

Something a little more basic for those who don't want a whole party happening on their fries. Â Some tasty bulkogi on some fries to go with a good beer.

Or the vegan Gravy Fries from <a href="http://seabirdskitchen.com/">Seabirds</a>Â food truck turned kitchen which was paired nicely with a brew from <a href="http://www.thebruery.com/">The Bruery</a>.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/photo-copy-3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-706" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/photo-copy-3.jpg" alt="Gravy Fries" width="598" height="598" />
</a>"Natural cut fries, mushroom gravy, fresh chives"

For those who are trying to enjoy fries and not have too much guilt about it. I mean, it's vegan so these fries are good for you, right?

But to this day, my taste buds stay loyal to the Garlic Feta Fries from <a href="https://twitter.com/garlicscape">GarlicScapes</a>:

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-432" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/gscapes2.jpg" alt="Garlic Feta Fries" width="638" height="638" /></a>

"Fries tossed in garlic with scape sauce and feta cheese"

Just thinking about these fries always make my mouth water. I love garlic and I love cheese, so I can't seem to find a more viable combo.
More on GarlicScapes <a href="http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/2013/08/11/kniight-riider/">here</a>!

Anyone in the Orange County area have any suggestions? Let me know. I'm always looking for good nomz especially when it revolves around fries! 
  
 
 

   ]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Craft Beer + Food Trucks</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/04/12/craft-beer-food-trucks/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 12 Apr 2014 09:28:15 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=726</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[What's my favorite part about living in Southern California? It'sÂ not the perfect weather or the ability to get from the beaches off the Pacific Coast Highway to the snowy mountains of Mammoth in a matter of hours. It's the fact that I can drive to at least five different breweriesÂ all withinÂ ten minutes, give or take, and enjoy a glass of beer paired with food from a food truck rightÂ outside the brewery. Or now my newfound favorite, watching Game of Thrones whileÂ enjoying a delicious pint and meal at aÂ brewery! I did not know such greatness could exist, until I lived it.

The growth of the craft beer industry cannot be ignored. We have breweries popping up left and right, kind of like we've seen with the coffee industry. Â While the coffee shops promote more of a solitary atmosphere, what's great about breweries is the sense of communityÂ being brought back to life.Â We evolved into a more disconnected society and breweries have been bringing people together.

BreweriesÂ have become a watering hole for many to gather and try out brews each place has to offer. <a href="http://www.thebruery.com/">The Bruery</a> Provisions, now <a href="http://www.provisionsmarkets.com/">Provisions Market</a>, in Old Towne Orange was once myÂ go-to placeÂ andÂ <a href="http://www.bootleggersbrewery.com/">Bootlegger's Brewery</a> in downtown Fullerton has been a staple, but the newly opened <a href="http://bottlelogic.com/">Bottle Logic Brewing</a> in Anaheim has now won me over and I have a whole new world of beers to explore. My favorite beer at <a href="http://www.bootleggersbrewery.com/">Bootlegger's</a> is their Knuckle Sandwich Double IPA, which is a limited release beer, so I usually stray away when it's not on tap (now). Bottle Logic Brewing, however, has their limited release Double IPA, Double Actuator, on tap right now! I'd like to taste it next to the Knuckle Sandwich, so I can decide which I like better.

[caption id="attachment_736" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/photo-2.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-736" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/photo-2.jpg?w=800" alt="The Bruery + Viking Truck" width="800" height="800" /></a> The Bruery + Viking Truck[/caption]

Now when I'm drinking a beer, I get hungry. NowÂ how perfectÂ is it to have a food truck outside prepared to serve you their specialty; you've got <a href="http://www.thevikingtruck.com/home">The Viking Truck </a>with their Loki and Dragon Eggs to <a href="http://burgermonster.net/">Burger Monster</a> and their Attack of the Killer Potato or <a href="https://twitter.com/garlicscape">GarlicScape</a> and their Garlic Feta Fries. Unfortunately, I have yet to experience <a href="http://kogibbq.com/">Kogi BBQ</a> at a brewery. You don't need to drive anywhere and decide where to eat, let alone drive drunk, youÂ just conveniently walk outside. Someone told me that food trucks aren't as big as they used to be in Southern California, but with the birth of many breweries, it's a match made in heaven and might even create more food trucks. Want to enjoy beer and food from the comfort of your own home? Then grab a growler and get food to-go!

[caption id="attachment_737" align="alignnone" width="800"]<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/photo.jpg"><img class="wp-image-737 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/photo.jpg?w=800" alt="Bottle Logic + Burger Monster" width="800" height="800" /></a> Bottle Logic + Burger Monster[/caption]

One day I was bummed that all the food trucks I was craving were not anywhere near me and I thought to myself, why can't I just go to a place that doesn't move? Then I realized there's some sort of thrill of scrolling through my Twitter (which I solely created for this purpose) feed and googling trucks, trying to figure out what food trucks are where and if I want to drive to them. Usually the jackpot is when my favorite food truck is at a brewery. My biggest jackpot thus far has been <a href="http://bottlelogic.com/">Bottle Logic Brewing</a> playing season three of Game of Thrones that led into the season premier of season fourÂ +Â the Double Actuator and their special medieval cask for the night 'Hodor,' which taste like horchata, + <a href="http://www.thevikingtruck.com/home">The Viking Truck</a> right outside!

The sayÂ good food brings people together? Now add good beer to it! I think now is the best time to live in Southern California if you can appreciate a good bite and a good pint. Eat local and drink local. I even hear the mayor of Anaheim plans to make the city the hub for craft beer in Orange County.

Craft beer is on the rise everywhere and has become more artful in many ways. Now do yourself a favor and get to your local brewery and grab a pint and a bite at a food truck!]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Prosciutto on my Mind</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/04/26/prosciutto-on-my-mind/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 26 Apr 2014 02:32:46 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=745</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[To the food I can't stop thinking about, I got you on my mind- the prosciutto sandwich. I can barely spell prosciutto, constantly double-checking if I need to add or remove a letter, but when it comes to eating it; well, don't mind if I do!

When I first fell for prosciutto, it was while I was in Tokyo. I struggled to decipherÂ the Japanese characters on the menu of what seemed to say "raw ham." Prosciutto. Salty goodness paired with fresh slices of avocado, atop a beef patty, lodged between two slices of bread. My mouth is watering as I recall this memory. It is, to this day, my favorite burger of all time and it was found in Japan at <a href="http://journal-cafe.jp/">J.S. Burger</a>, which I wrote about in an old post, <a href="http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/2013/06/08/always-nom/">Always Nom</a>.

AÂ few weeks ago I finallyÂ went to what is probably the most hole-in-the-wall spot I've been to in Orange County- <a href="http://www.elgauchomarket.com/">El Gaucho Meat Market</a>. It is an Argentine market, tucked away in Anaheim, not too far from Disneyland. A coworker of mine hyped it up to me, mainly the unlimited chimichurri sauce you can drench your food in.Â I put it on my list of places to eat to eventually get to. Now a customer comes in, they discuss the deliciousness of El Gaucho, customer mentions PROSCIUTTO sandwich, now I'm listening!

El Gaucho is found off Lincoln on the 57, on State College. It doesn't look like anything special. It looks like a random independently-owned convenience store, if anything. You may even doubt the recommendation when you stepÂ foot in the place. You step to the right and oh hey! there's a food place in here!

When you order you find a plethora of jars containing chimichurri next to the register, a key part to your meal. You order empanadas, your appetizer. I got a spinach one, slathered it with chimichurri, wasn't disappointed.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/1396305497-312943-20.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-746 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/1396305497-312943-20.jpg?w=800" alt="Spinach Empanada" width="800" height="600" /></a>

Then you order your sandwich, one of the greatestÂ sandwiches to ever grace your mouth. They have traditional argentine meat like the milanesa, breaded beef, and then they have the prosciutto sandwich.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/photo-3.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-747 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/04/photo-3.jpg?w=800" alt="Milanesa &amp; Prosciutto" width="800" height="600" /></a>

I swapped halves with my boyfriend so that I could try both, but I enjoyed my choice much more. While they both were good, I was so excited to have a thick serving of prosciutto! I'm used to it being used like bacon, more of an accent to a greater good of flavors, or like the "cherry on top." This time it was the main event and I enjoyed every moment of it! It immediately became my favorite sandwich.

If you find yourself in the Anaheim area, maybe you're headed to Disneyland or going to one of the local breweries, skip the corporate-ran fast-food joints and stop by El Gaucho Meat Market. They do close at 7 p.m., so be aware of that.

Grab yourself some empanadas, a sandwich (prosciutto, if you love it as much as I do), the jar of chimichurri,Â smother your food with chimichurri, enjoy!

</ul>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Current Muse: The Speculoos Special</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/06/18/current-muse-the-speculoos-special/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 18 Jun 2014 01:20:31 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=758</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I've always had a weak spot for waffles. I used to love Eggo waffles growing up, unaware of the authenticity this waffle lacked. I grasped on to my love for them up until my first year of college in Chicago; I can recall times I've thrown waffles in my toaster in a rush, only to eat them nearly as cold as they started as I walked the snow-covered streets. IÂ was also fascinated by their themed waffles, like when they had Lego Eggo's or Pirates of the Caribbean.

My sophistication for waffles have grown since then and I have been reunited with my love for waffles through Southern California's gourmet waffle truck- <a href="http://www.wafflesdeliege.com/">Waffles de Liege</a>. It all started when I got home from a long day of work, attached to my bed. I came across <a href="https://twitter.com/wafflesdeliege">@wafflesdeliege</a>Â on Twitter and after a few clicks around their site and an observation of their menu, I declared that I would not be leaving my apartment unless I was getting waffles.

Leave my apartment I did, a waffle I did get. <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/wafflesdeliege.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-819" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/wafflesdeliege.jpg?w=474" alt="Speculoos Special" width="474" height="355" /></a>I almost got the Nutella Classic- fresh bananas and Nutella on the Liege waffle, but the guy on the window suggested I try the Speculoos Special instead. I'm not a diehard Nutella fan. Heck, I don't even know when's the last time I've consumed Nutella. It was the same concept, except with Speculoos instead of Nutella. He claimed that it is a better suitor for their Liege waffle and how could I say no to better flavor?Â It was that night, I fell in love with Speculoos and the Liege waffle. What are they? You'll find it on the <a href="http://www.wafflesdeliege.com/faq/">FAQ</a>Â section of their website.

The waffle was crisp on the outside, yet soft and doughy in the middle, the perfect texture. It has the right amount of crunch.Â The Speculoos, which taste like a gingerbread cookie in butter form, complimentedÂ the waffle likeÂ they were soul mates. And the banana?Yes, it was delicious amongst the duo, but it is there for me to feel like I'm being healthy. To be honest, I was nervous that I was getting myself an overwhelmingly sweet dessert, but it was just right! From the moment it hit my tongue, my taste buds did a celebration dance.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Smorgasburg Food Flea Market | Brooklyn</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/06/11/smorgasburg-food-flea-market-brooklyn/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 11 Jun 2014 08:27:19 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=760</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Holy CRAP! Where to start? I'm the girl who has dreams about food so when I heard about <a href="http://www.smorgasburg.com/">Smorgasburg</a> in Brooklyn, it easily became my main focus for our trip.

Smorgasburg is a food flea market that takes place on the Williamsburg waterfront on Saturdays and on theÂ Brooklyn Bridge Parkâs Pier 5 on Sundays.

I evenÂ booked an <a href="https://www.airbnb.com/">AirBnB</a> in Williamsburg on Friday night just so IÂ could be within walking distance of it onÂ Saturday morning because unfortunately, Saturday was the end of the New York trip and we had to be in Chinatown by 2 p.m. to catch a bus to visit my friends in Maryland.

With that being said, Smorgasburg opens at 11 a.m. so my boyfriend and I had about an hour and a half to devour anything and everything we could possibly get our hands on.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-770 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/lumpiashack.jpg?w=580" alt="lumpiashack" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://www.lumpia-shack.com/">Lumpia Shack</a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg">
</a>I started off with the Lumpia Shack. Lumpia=filipino eggrolls. It's not everyday you see a food establishment solely dedicated to lumpia or even filipino food in a setting like this; you usually have to make a point to seek them out.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-771 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/lumpiashack2.jpg?w=580" alt="lumpiashack2" width="580" height="389" /></a>IÂ got the sampler which included pork, truffled adobo mushroom, and peking duck. Pork was hands down the winner. Your basic lumpia will typically include pork and classics are often hard to beat. I was very impressed that there was aÂ vegetarian option and a vegetarian option done well!Â Lumpia is probably the gateway to filipino food. Just about everyone knows what eggrolls areÂ and here they are, just with a different name.Â I think I like lumpia the best but mainly because there is typically a vinegar, soy sauce and garlic mixture to dip them in. If you've never had filipino food and want to take baby steps in trying some, start here!<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg">
</a>

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/queencobra.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-773" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/queencobra.jpg?w=580" alt="Queen Cobra" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://queencobrathai.tumblr.com/">Queen Cobra Thai
</a>While I went for the lumpia, the boyÂ found himself at Queen Cobra Thai.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/queencobra2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-774" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/queencobra2.jpg?w=580" alt="Grilled pork skewers with Thai spicy Jim-Jaew sauce" width="580" height="389" /></a>I probably wouldn't have made my way to this booth on my own, but the grilled pork skewers with Thai spicy Jim-Jaew sauce that he got was something I definitely would've missed out on. The pork was tender, easy to pull apart, andÂ perfectly balanced between sweet and salty. It would be the perfect companion to aÂ beer that we unfortunately lacked.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/thegoodbatch2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-781" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/thegoodbatch2.jpg?w=580" alt="The Good Batch" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://thegoodbatch.com/">The Good Batch
</a>IÂ wished I had more of this. After roaming around the Smorgasburg grounds, I was trying to mentally create a list of foodÂ to be devoured. I tried to strategically plan which foods should be consumed in what order for maximum capacity in my belly. As I tried to devise a master food plan, I found my boyfriend at this vendor. My boyfriend and I are not huge on sweets, but here he was, getting an ice cream sandwich. A very delicious ice cream sandwich I might add. We were still at the beginning of our food ventures and I did not want to be taken out this early in the game. Ice cream would have been the rain of my parade. Dat cookie doe.
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/thegoodbatch.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-780" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/thegoodbatch.jpg?w=580" alt="Goodwich" width="580" height="389" /></a>The Goodwich-Â Oat chocolate chunk cookie, sea salt, drizzled fudge and vanilla ice cream. If I was in the mood for sweets, that would have been everything I could ever want. It's not too sweet, which is key for me and salt involved is always a good thing. The sweetnessÂ was not overbearing and the flavors hit all the right notes.
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/homefrite.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-767" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/homefrite.jpg?w=580" alt="Home Frite" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://homefrite.com/">Home Frite
</a>Fries, my heart and soul. When I saw them, I just knew. I also knew that it could potentially weigh me down just as the ice cream would, but my love for fries concurs all. My biggest dilemma, however, was whether I wanted lemon garlic aioli or malt aioli.<a href="http://homefrite.com/">
<img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-768" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/homefrite2.jpg?w=580" alt="Original with Malt Aioli" width="580" height="386" /></a>After consulting with the kind lady at the booth whom also displayed stress for having to decide between the two, she told me that if I like malt vinegar, it has a really strong malt vinegar flavor. I was SOLD! My concern was that the malt aioli would be more of a hint of malt flavors and she eased all my worries away. It was like putting malt vinegar on your fries, with the convenience of a dip, and not having to sacrifice the crispiness of your fries for the malt flavor. The Home Frite's site states "we make the crispiest fries and amazing dipping sauces" and that they do.
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/takumitaco.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-778" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/takumitaco.jpg?w=580" alt="Takumi Taco" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://tacotruck.marketmymarket.com/">Takumi Taco
</a>Raw fish meets taco? The one booth that made me feel like I was back in California. Here on the West Coast, we see a lot of Asian-Mexican fusions-from <a href="http://kogibbq.com/">Kogi BBQ</a> to <a href="http://www.jogasakiburrito.com/">Jogasaki Sushi Burrito</a>- that thrive and well, I don't hate it!
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/takumitaco2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-779" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/takumitaco2.jpg?w=580" alt="Spicy Tuna Taco" width="580" height="389" /></a>The spicy tuna taco from Takumi Taco taco is another Asian-Mexican fusion I do not hate. The spicy tuna tasted fresh and wasn't too spicy. I did enjoy that they provide a bed of tortilla chips beneath the taco. In my opinion, it is there to catch any spicy tuna that may fall when you bite into your taco, as things always fall out of your taco when you bite into it. Your spicy tuna will fall to yourÂ convenienceÂ atop aÂ tortilla chip for your consumption. No tuna shall be wasted! Clever.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/kombucha.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-769" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/kombucha.jpg?w=580" alt="Kombucha Brooklyn" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://www.kombuchabrooklyn.com/">Kombucha Brooklyn
</a>Watermelon. I did have a delicious calamansi basil tea from Lumpia Shack, but all that food needed more drank. I'm a fan of vinegar. Yes, I enjoy it a lot. Now a whole booth dedicated to kombucha is the next best thing! I would've even gotten a growler if I lived in New York. I just have to say that they had watermelon and since Beyonce been sippin' watermelon, I just had to do the same. I did see that the other flavor was a sour cherry tart or something? It probably was just as good too! But while I listened to these guys talk, I overheard that everyone loves the watermelon one and have been waiting for it's return. It's refreshing for that summer heat, with a little bit of kick from the fermentation of the tea that takes place, while reaping all the health benefits from kombucha! You can read about the health benefits on Kombucha Brooklyn's <a href="http://www.kombuchabrooklyn.com/kombucha-benefits.html">benefit's page</a>.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-761" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg?w=580" alt="Bassanova" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="https://www.facebook.com/bassanovanyc">Bassanova Ramen
</a>The nontraditional ramen. The Japanese always do a good job at visuals and making things look cute and appealing. They all wore matching striped shirts and seemed very inviting. Their booth boasted a bunch ofÂ awards, but we kept walking past them. I think my boyfriend and I put ramen towards the end of our eating journey at Smorgasburg because we didn't want to be full from all those noodles and broth.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bossanova2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-764" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bossanova2.jpg?w=580" alt="Green Curry Ramen" width="580" height="389" /></a>Broth? When my boyfriend picked up our ramen, boy was I surprised to not see any broth whatsoever. The whole point of ramen is the broth!Â I have a love for tsukemen, dipping ramen, but lately I've found myself deeply attached to soup. And this ramen didn't even have anything for me to dip these noodles in too! Now what the hell is this thing? Because it definitely was not ramen. The more I ate, the more I found forgiveness in me for this so-called "ramen" concoction. The noodles were easy to eat, just as if you were lifting them out of a soup, the firmness of the noodles were right, and the flavors were all there without dealing with the mess that can beÂ curry and ramen. This nonconformist dish grew on me and if I could have some right now, I would definitely find my way there. Unfortunately, I am back in California while this ramen is livin' it up in the Big Apple.
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bitesizekitchen.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-762" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bitesizekitchen.jpg?w=580" alt="Bite Size Kitchen" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://www.bitesizekitchen.com/">Bite Size Kitchen
</a>To be honest, this was the least memorable dish of all. Not saying it wasn't good, but I am saying I recall being wrapped up at some other booth while the boy swung by with this little bun.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bitesizekitchen2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-763" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bitesizekitchen2.jpg?w=580" alt="Duck Bun" width="580" height="389" /></a>I believe this was a duck bun. That is all I can remember. Maybe I could have loved it; the menu on their website looks good, but I was seriously immersed in something else during this point that I cannot recall the flavors at all. I am also not a fan of duck, so that could also be it. My boyfriend had no complaints.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dosa.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-765" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dosa.jpg?w=580" alt="Dosa Royale" width="580" height="389" /></a><a href="http://dosaroyale.com/">Dosa Royale
</a>I've gotten Indian food many times before, but have never heard of a dosa. I wasn't even going to get a dosa. I didn't know what the heck it was and was going to get a samosa instead, but then I saw it...
<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dosa2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-766" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dosa2.jpg?w=580" alt="Spinach &amp; Paneer Dosa" width="580" height="386" /></a>Suddenly, I needed it. I kept going to the booth and would walk away, but when it came close to having to leave, I knew I couldn't leave without trying this huge thing of the unknown. I was intrigued by it's size and how they made it. I got the spinach and paneer dosa and it was good! I kind of assumed the spinach and paneer would have been curried; it's the only way I've had it at an Indian place. The spinach and paneer were actually fresh, so it was more of a refreshing rather than heavy dish. After all that other food, I struggled with this one, but it was worth it. What is a dosa? According to their site, aÂ dosa is a savory thin crepe made from a fermented batter of rice and black lentils and is naturally gluten free.

The Ramen Burger line still reigned all the other lines. I was once intrigued by this concoction, but now I choose to not fall into the hype. I've heard it's okay, or maybe I just don't want to stand in that long of a line, especially with time constraints. I love my ramen and I love my burgers, separate.

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/ramenburger.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-775" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/ramenburger.jpg?w=580" alt="Ramen Burger line" width="580" height="389" /></a>

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/smorg1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-776" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/smorg1.jpg?w=580" alt="Smogasburg" width="580" height="389" /></a>

<a href="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/smorg2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-777" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/smorg2.jpg?w=580" alt="Smorgasburg" width="580" height="389" /></a>
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/bassanova.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-772 size-large" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/manhattan.jpg?w=580" alt="Manhattan" width="580" height="389" /></a>Aside from being a hub for good food, Smorgasburg provides for a lovely view of the Manhattan skyline. All in all, Smorgasburg was a good note to end our New York trip on. I even purchased some whoopie pies from <a href="https://batterandcream.com/">Batter and Cream</a>Â to give to my friends, which they enjoyed, and some chimichurri from <a href="http://elvioschimi.com/">Elvio's</a>.

I would love to live in Brooklyn just for the sake of going to Smorgasburg every weekend.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>To the Ice Caves!</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/06/19/to-the-ice-caves/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 19 Jun 2014 07:45:05 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=824</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Forget the Batcave, the Ice Caves will be the only thing that comes to mind when you hear the word cave.

In theÂ upper left corner ofÂ the U.S. lies America's best kept secret, the Pacific Northwest. Hidden behind the reputation of a supposedÂ 24/7 rainfall lies the abundance of earth's natural wonders. Just ninety minutes north of Seattle, you'll find one of the many places in Washington that makes you feel like you just stumbled into something out of a fairy tale-Â The Big Four Ice Caves in Granite Falls.

Since Southern California experienced heat waves before summer ever started, IÂ began dreaming of being emerged into a forest, with an infinite amount of trees shielding me from the sun and a rich quality of air.

On this trip, I was hungry for adventure and exploration rather food.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0120-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-827" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0120-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0134-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-828" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0134-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0140-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-829" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0140-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0148-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-830" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0148-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0158-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-831" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0158-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0172-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-832" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0172-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0173-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-833" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0173-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0178-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-834" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0178-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0184-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-835" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0184-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0199-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-836" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0199-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0267-copy.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-839" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/dsc_0267-copy.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a>

<item>
  <title>Chimichurri, a Love Affair.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/06/28/chimichurri-a-love-affair/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 28 Jun 2014 09:03:22 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=851</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[While my boyfriend held fears ofÂ ourÂ plane crashing into the deep blue sea, I held the fear of my chimichurri being denied by the TSA.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/elvio1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-857" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/06/elvio1.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="474" /></a>On my recent trip to the East Coast, the only souvenir I brought home with me was a jar of <a href="http://elvioschimi.com/">Elvio's Chimichurri</a>. I purchased two jars from Elvio's Chimi at Smorgasburg- one as a gift to my friends I would be visiting later and one jar for myself. The one for myself was a gamble because from that moment on, I was paranoid this jar was full of too much liquid thatÂ I wouldn't be able to bring it on my flight home. Â Four days after my purchase, you could not imagine the relief I felt crossing security check with my chimichurri. Success!

Well up until a week ago, I didn't open that jar.Â Maybe because I knew that once I opened it, it would be gone. With the basis of vinegar and garlic, you can put chimichurri onÂ everything really and it'll only make whatever you're eating a million times better! I've now been making a point to cook something up, just so I can use the chimichurri.

Elvio's is a family business with a recipe inherited from Argentina. Learn more about their story and where you can grab a jar for yourself to experience the deliciousness your palate has been lacking on their website,Â <a href="http://elvioschimi.com/">Elvio's Chimi</a>.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>What's better than shabu shabu? Organic shabu-shabu!</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/07/03/whats-better-than-shabu-shabu-organic-shabu-shabu/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 03 Jul 2014 07:27:07 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=864</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[On a questÂ to find a shabu shabu restaurant open late, I stumbled upon a new shabu shabu joint that opened two months agoÂ in Anaheim Hills. This one wasn't open late, but what really sold me was that this new restaurant boasted organic ingredients. I had to go the next day!

<a href="http://trueshabu.com/">True Shabu</a>Â brings a whole new experience to the shabu shabu world. For those who don't know, shabu shabu is Japanese dish that consists of cooking thinly sliced meat in a hot-pot full of boiling water, usually a broth that you can enjoy as soup. While frequenting Asian restaurants or any restaurant for that matter, I sometimes ponder the integrity of the food. Yes, the end product is delicious, but I don't know what goes into it. I avoid the typical fast food joints, but could I be investing money into something that might be just as bad for me? Alas, a shabu place built for the conscientious!

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/1404241417-262839-14.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-865" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/1404241417-262839-14.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="355" /></a>

True Shabu promotes no antibiotics or hormones in their meats, no MSG, no preservatives, offer gluten-free noodles, quinoa, and evenÂ give you the option of grass-fed meats. All these things I never thought about while getting my shabu fix. Now it makes me wonder what I was really eating at the other places.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/1404241402-728654-54.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-866" src="http://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/1404241402-728654-54.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="355" /></a>I went with a friend whose favorite food is shabu shabu. Shabu for meÂ probablyÂ makes top five. When walking into True Shabu, the atmosphere automaticallyÂ wins us over; it's so new, modern and clean. Our server helps us behind the bar and explains to us the menu. The prices are a bit higher and they charge you an extra 2 dollars if you want to make it a broth, but the price actually balances out with other places if you visit for lunch. Their base meat, Â the prime chuck, is the same quality you would get at other places for choosing a ribeye and it's even better becauseÂ you're not getting hormones and antibiotics!

I was busy trying to take a few shots of my meal, while my friend already got a mouthful in, raving on how good it was. I almost was gonna ditch the photos, but I knew I had to share this restaurant to the world if it was THAT good. It was THAT good! Their sauces- goma and ponzu are made in-house daily. The goma is 100 percent ground sesame seeds and the sugar in the ponzu is replaced with pomegranate juice that gives the citrusy flavors just the right boostÂ for the perfect flavors. I usually don't even care for the goma, but I fell in love with this one. The meat, paired with the ponzu... once it hit my taste buds, they did a little dance. Maybe a big dance! Everything tasted so much better than I could have ever imagined. It was like a whole new experience between shabu shabu and I, like when you've finally met "the one." This was it.

For all the shabu shabu lovers out there and for those who want to try something new to eat in Orange County, head to True Shabu in Anaheim.Â They make you feel like you're dining in a five-star restaurant and I have to say, the organic and natural touch to the ingredients really make a difference that you won't know you were missing until you get yourself a meal here.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Battle of the Neighboring Double IPAs</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/?p=873</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 03 Jul 2014 09:02:00 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=873</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[From the momentÂ I got my handsÂ aroundÂ a pint of Double Actuator, right after my first sip I said, "I want to try this next to Knuckle Sandwich!" Why? Because it was reminiscent on KS.

Both beers are double IPA's that hail in neighboring cities in Orange County. Knuckle Sandwich comes out of Bootlegger's Brewery in Fullerton while Double Actuator takes home at Bottle Logic in Anaheim. Through my exploration of local beers, Knuckle Sandwich easily became my favorite beer. For a beer with 10% ABV, this was an easy drink and a nice break from your basic India Pale Ales. Â I found myself frequenting Bootlegger's often when Knuckle Sandwich was on tap and straying away when it was not.

I strayed away to Bottle Logic and fell in love with Double Actuator, also 10% ABV. I could only faintly remember the citrusy hops of Knuckle Sandwich as I enjoyed hops basking in fruitiness. Now which did I like better? I wanted to know. As seasonal beers, they kept being on tap at alternate times dodging my agenda. When finally, Knuckle Sandwich and Double Actuator finally revealed themselves to me simultaneously, I grabbed them bottles.

KS tastes heavy as thick. DA drinks more crisp, with hops pulling through more than KS.

Knuckle Sandwich will always be my favorite, but it no longer tastes as I remember it to be. A friend noted that it tasted more malty and not as refreshing and bright as a West Coast style would be. KSÂ still holds a 99 on RateBeer.com while Double Actuator only holds a 72, but the fact is the consistency hasn't seemed to be there for me since it's return in May. I can count on Double Actuator tasting like Double Actuator each time. I've heard they've been making some tweaks with KS so Â that could be why.

I'll keep trying Knuckle Sandwich. I know things change, but I loved you as you were.]]></content:encoded>

  <title>The worst vegetarian for Sheep's Head in Iceland</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/?p=910</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 09 Jul 2014 08:08:00 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=910</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I'm always nostalgic about Iceland-vast natural landscapes, cafÃ©s that turn into bars, the people- but the one thing I could've lived without was eating a Sheep's face in Iceland. When in Rome, right?

While having a night out in downtown ReykjavÃ­k, locals approach spotting out the Americans as I try to take a picture. Come with us, is pretty much what they said. It's been nearly four years since I been there and I was probably drinking so forgive me, but I'm pretty sure what happened was that we all hopped into a taxi so what we could get sheep's head. 



They take us to a bar for some shots of BrennivÃ­n, otherwise known as "Black Death." It taste like black licorice, a popular flavor in Iceland.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>The Final Adventure of The Year| Road Trip</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/12/20/the-final-adventure-of-the-year-road-trip/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 20 Dec 2014 09:36:49 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=931</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[In a few hours, 5 a.m. to be exact, my roommate and I shall load up his Subaru with some camping gear and my cat to and make our way to the redwoods in Humboldt. Good times. Good adventures.

Be prepared. The last stretch of 2014 is coming to an end and what better way to celebrate the year than with one final epic adventure. This year has been amazing. I say that with 100 percent truth. In these past months alone, I've done soo muchâcamped atÂ Yosemite and the Sequoias; drank my way through San Diego Beer Week and wasÂ a part ofÂ the world's largest bottle share;Â lived out my teenage dreams with seeing bands like Black Dahlia Murder, Saves the Day, and Death from Above 1979 to discovering and seeing a new favorite band like Tame Impala. I'll definitely have to do some posts with photos from the national park explorations.

Here's a photo from my trip to the Sequoias at 7,600 feet in elevation to give you a taste of what's to come:
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/7600ft.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-932 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/7600ft.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="495" /></a>
<blockquote>âAlways explore the world with newÂ eyes, dream of places youâve never imagined and discover a love so perfect it was almost never meant to be.â -R.M. Drake</blockquote>
Time to catnap before A D V E N T U R E TIME.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Road Trip | Day 2 #MJWINGINIT</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/12/21/road-trip-day-2-mjwinginit/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2014 22:11:49 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/2014/12/21/road-trip-day-2-mjwinginit/</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Although I could barely manage to see my surroundings, every now and then I could see the silhouette of the redwoods towering over me and that alone made me feel safe, protected, and content.
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8836.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8836.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_8836.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
This trip has been full of clouds and rain preventing Mat and I from camping in the redwood forest, but not from exploring a little. We reached the redwoods in total darkness, but catching a glimpse of its silhouette from time to time made me feel at peace. 
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8838.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8838.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_8838.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
We attempted to go to <a href="http://russianriverbrewing.com/">Russian River Brewing</a> to get a Pliny. I was mostly hoping  to finally try Supplication, but we both didn't want to wait in line, so we decided to go to <a href="https://avbc.com/">Anderson Valley Brewing</a>. 
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8837.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8837.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_8837.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
Anderson Valley is located in Boonville, California and are the saints behind creating my favorite beer- The Kimmie, the Yink, and the Holy Gose. A sour, salty, refreshing beer at 4.7% that's perfect for drinking in the summer heat. They've also come out with a Blood Orange Gose that is essentially a beermosa, perfect for breakfast, which  I happened to have at 6 a.m. yesterday.
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8767.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_8767.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_8767.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
We're still on the road. I'll give you a more in-depth post in the future on Anderson Valley Brewing.

 I've been hashtagging #mjwinginit (Mat + Jante wingin' it) on <a href="http://instagram.com/janteziarra">Instagram</a>.

Always somewhere. Never nowhere.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Road Trip | Day 6 No Beer, No Food, Just Trees.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2014/12/27/road-trip-day-6-no-beer-no-food-just-trees/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2014 04:43:53 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.wordpress.com/2014/12/27/road-trip-day-6-no-beer-no-food-just-trees/</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Whenever I travel back to the Pacific Northwest, life gets stripped down. My love for beer and food get placed aside. That little campfire inside me that longs to explore turns into a wild brushfire and I am not content until I am engulfed by trees. Once I am there, I don't want to leave. I feel the pull of nature luring me, seducing me, telling me to stay when I know I have to go. Maybe it's best that I haven't gone on a hike alone while I'm here because once immersed in the woods, I might've fallen victim to the spell it keeps trying to cast, trying to keep me for itself.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_9227.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_9227.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_9227.jpg" /></a>
It's my last night up north. Mat and I leave for California tomorrow morning. I got to explore Vancouver, B.C. today. The lack of daylight has been cutting my explorations short on this trip, never fully reaching my intended final destination, but the journey trying to get there is really what it's all about. It just means I'll have to return and try again and make more memories. I mean, what would life be if you got everything right the first time? One of life's pleasures is experience.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_9229.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_9229.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_9229.jpg" /></a>
Dear <a href="http://www.vancouvertrails.com/trails/dog-mountain/">Dog Mountain</a> in North Vancouver,

I will return and get to the top of you next time!

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_9221.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2014/12/img_9221.jpg" alt="/home/wpcom/public_html/wp-content/blogs.dir/c13/37742241/files/2014/12/img_9221.jpg" /></a>
With Love,
Jante]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Going Down To Mexico, Gonna Eat A Lot Of Tacos.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/01/23/going-down-to-mexico-gonna-eat-a-lot-of-tacos/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 23 Jan 2015 06:49:24 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/2015/01/23/going-down-to-mexico-gonna-eat-a-lot-of-tacos/</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Where does saying yes get you? On a flight to Mexico with new friends. 
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0106-2.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0106-2.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0106-2.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
We've got me, the wanderlusting transplant from Hawai'i; Kaitlyn, the Australian gal who spent her semester abroad in Long Beach; Jasmine, the aspiring sports journalist out of Laguna Beach, and her boyfriend Teddy, the professional skimboarder. All of whom are currently on a plane ride out of San Diego to Cabo San Lucas. 
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0107.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0107.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0107.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
Kaitlyn and I have never been to Mexico so as of now, our main goal is to eat a lot of tacos. 
<br /><br /><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0138-0.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0138-0.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0138-0.jpg" class="alignnone size-full" /></a>
[instagram url=http://instagram.com/p/yN882iqHaY]]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Once Upon A Time In Mexico | Day 2 #KJgettintacos</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/01/23/once-upon-a-time-in-mexico-day-2-kjgettintacos/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 23 Jan 2015 19:57:29 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=962</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[We made it through customs and finally stepped foot outside of the airport, to be greeted with a beer and a shot of tequila. So this is Mexico? I felt like I was on the Vegas strip.
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0139.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0139.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0139.jpg" /></a>
Teddy had been to Mexico a bunch of times before and have friends who live here so we got a ride into town from his friend, Chimmy. We got tacos!

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0156.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0156.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0156.jpg" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0141.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0141.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0141.jpg" /></a>
We spent the night on the beach where we met a group of five lovely ladies hailing from Spokane, Washington. Jasmine had offered to take a picture of them and in exchange, they bought us a round of drinks, so we joined them. These ladies are beautiful people and I am really grateful that we ran into them.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0157.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0157.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0157.jpg" /></a>
As much as I love beer and tacos, my favorite part of this city so far is being able to get a giant fruit cup right outside of our hotel.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0158.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0158.jpg" alt="2015/01/img_0158.jpg" /></a>
Currently battling a head cold or allergies, so my brain is mush and I'm having a hard time putting this post together.

#KJgettintacos on Instagram.
[instagram url=http://instagram.com/p/yPtCVoqHQ8]]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Why Not Climb It? | Day 3 Mount Solmar</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/01/29/why-not-climb-it-day-3-mount-solmar/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 29 Jan 2015 23:55:17 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=971</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA["Let's climb Mt. Solmar," she said.
"Okay," I say, followed by, "What's that?"

I look at Kaitlyn's phone and see that it's that very mountain in the postcard I had just finished writing.

We had to missionsÂ for the day: Get to the post office to send out our postcards and to climb Mt. Solmar.

We successfully found the post office- postcards stamped and dropped into the mailbox. I noticed <a href="http://www.tacosgardenias.com/">Tacos Gardenias</a> near the post office, a place I kept hearing had really good fish tacos, so we feast. We started to learn that we were getting full off just the chips and salsas alone so order minimal- ceviche to share and a fish taco each. I was Â tempted to add in a shrimp taco, but whatever sickness I was battling was keeping my appetite small. Sigh.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0306.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-974 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0306.jpg?w=660" alt="Tacos Gardenia" width="660" height="495" /></a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0315.jpg">
</a>Tacos Gardenias lived up to it's rep! The taco pescado (fish taco) was airy, with the right amount of crisp, the ceviche had just enough salt and lime to enhance the blend of shrimp, tomato and avocado.

With our bellies full, we set out on ourÂ mission to find the way up Mount Solmar. Follow the marina until the end, then you'll find a trail going up. If you decide to climb Mount Solmar, go right! We strolled left at first and ended up across of where we wanted to be. Walk to the right of the marina until it ends, you'll hit a beach and alas, Mount Solmar!

We hiked up barefoot majority of the time which made it easier. Definitely not recommended for the fragile of feet. Once we reached the top, we cheersed our Pacificos and sat overlooking where the Sea of Cortez and Pacific Ocean meet. We made it and it was beautiful. Now the hard part of the hike was getting down.<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0309.jpg">
<img class="alignnone wp-image-977 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0315.jpg?w=660" alt="Top of Mt. Solmar" width="660" height="495" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0309.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-976 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0309.jpg?w=660" alt="Divorce Beach" width="660" height="495" /></a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0308.jpg">
</a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0308.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-975 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/img_0308.jpg?w=660" alt="The Path Down" width="660" height="495" /></a>

We made our way to the popular tourist destination, Playa del Amor or "Lover's Beach," and took in the view. We went for a brief swim and eventually found ourselves aboard aÂ glass bottom boat taxi that was full of men. We didn't say it out loud to each other while on the boat, but Kaitlyn and I later discussed how we were thinking we maybe made a mistake by getting on the boat. We could have easily been taking elsewhere, against our will. Instead, we met a generous guy who wasÂ also visiting Cabo that wanted aÂ picture with us and ended up paying for our taxi fare.Â <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/vscocam-photo-1.jpg">
<img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-978" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/01/vscocam-photo-1.jpg?w=660" alt="Sail Home" width="660" height="495" />
</a>

Some people live in fear but there is no reason to fear what cannot be seen, for sometimes the greatest things lie within the realm of the unknown.

Kaitlyn and IÂ did the entire day on a whim, but it was the greatest of experiences. We met kind-hearted souls along the way that could have turned out bad. While at the top of Mount Solmar, a man offered to take our picture and I skeptically handed him my phone, knowing he could easily run away with it. He took our picture and gave it back. He and his friend were also tourists, visiting from Acapulco. There was also the boat ride that we didn't have to pay for. We were so ecstatic on how nice people are in a country that people are weary about going to.

Once we descended on the beach, we strolled into a random hotel heated pool and went for a swim. Afterwards, we found a cute little coffee shop that smelled of biscuits. It was a day full of the simplerÂ things in life, something that I live for.

While climbing that mountain, Kaitlyn told me that I gave her hope for when she's older because I'm still out doing things, going on adventures, living my life. At 21 now, she thought it'd be over over for her when she's 25. I just turned 27 and I told her this is the first time I have ever looked forward to getting older because there is still so much to do and so much time to do so! Life doesn't end when you get older, it just gets better.
[instagram url=http://instagram.com/p/yS9WUPqHWQ]]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Yo Quiero Mexico</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/02/06/yo-quiero-mexico/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 06 Feb 2015 07:01:44 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=1002</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[After so many adventures during winter break, I'm finally tied down- five classes, work and an internship.

My trip to Mexico was the most unplanned trip I had ever been on.Â My friend Kaitlyn couldn't extend her visa to stay in the states for another semester so is filling the last of her stay here full of trips. In order for her to have another 30 days in the states, she had to leave the country so she asked if I wanted to go to Mexico and I said, "Sure." Next thing you know, my ticket was booked and there I was with Mexico in my future.

It is easily one my most memorable, unexpected adventures so far. Built lasting friendships, established new friendships, had tacos for days, churro rellenos, beer, the beach, no complaints!

I do wish I took more photos, but sometimes exploring is more enjoyable when you don't have to see everything through a camera lens and you just live in the moment. <a href="http://youtu.be/5gx5z35Xpic">Think Sean Penn in The Secret Life of Walter Mitty.</a>
<blockquote><i><a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001774/">Walter Mitty</a></i>: When are you going to take it?
<i><a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000576/">Sean O'Connell</a></i>: Sometimes I don't. If I like a moment, for me, personally, I don't like to have the distraction of the camera. I just want to stay in it.
<i><a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001774/">Walter Mitty</a></i>: Stay in it?
<i><a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000576/">Sean O'Connell</a></i>: Yeah. Right there. Right here.</blockquote>
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0003-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1008" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0003-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="Cabo San Lucas" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0008-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1006" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0008-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="Cabo San Lucas" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0007-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1007" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0007-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="DSC_0007 copy" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0015-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1005" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0015-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="Cabo San Lucas" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0020-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1003" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0020-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="Cabo San Lucas" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0016-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1004" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/dsc_0016-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="Cabo San Lucas" width="660" height="442" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>HallÃ³ Heimur!</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/03/14/hallo-heimur/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 14 Mar 2015 09:26:04 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">https://janteziarra.wordpress.com/?p=1012</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[In 90 days, I will finally be back in Iceland. Unfortunately, just for a few days.<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/03/jzis.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1013" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/03/jzis.jpg" alt="Somewhere in Island." width="600" height="403"></a>

Why? Because I've got all of Europe to see! I will be doing something very ambitious and travel through ScandInavia and all of Western Europe within two months. My biggest concern is falling madly in love with a city in the beginning of my trip and not wanting to go anywhere else. I just have to be stern with myself and keep going.

After Iceland, I go to Norway, a country I already know I will love because of it's natural landscapes. From there, I go to Sweden to celebrate midsommar, or summer solstice, from June 19 - 21. I love culture and celebration around nature, but America hardly places any focus on the longest day of the year and the start of summer, so I decided I'd like to be a part of a country that places value on a day full of sun.

From there, I work my way to Denmark to celebrate sankthansaften, or St. John's Eve, on June 23 where they make a large bonfire for the celebration! I get to thank <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6lwDQxlPap8">Anthony Bourdain for showing me that on Parts Unknown</a>. It was during his visit to Copenhagen that I decided I must go there to witness this firsthand!

From Scandinavia, I work my way down through Europe, emphasis on beer cities and nature. I'm afraid each city will need an extension, however, time and money does not allow for it. I have been trying to plan this trip&nbsp;for over 3 years now and after failure after failure trying to plan it with someone, I decided I had to just do it in order for it to get done.
<blockquote>
<h1 class="sCaption" title="Edited">"The most dangerous risk of all - the risk of spending your life not doing what you want on the bet you can buy yourself the freedom to do it later."</h1>
</blockquote>
My trip is still in the works of planning. I intend to <a href="https://www.couchsurfing.com/">CouchSurf&nbsp;</a>the vast majority of my trip. What better way to learn the city than through the eyes of a local?

If you have any advice for me or you're somewhere abroad and would like to possibly meet up for a cup of coffee, beer or go explore the outdoors, please leave me a comment or send a message my way! Europe is a whole new world for me and I just know cities I should visit not necessarily know what I should do,&nbsp;so let me know of any must-sees or must-dos!]]></content:encoded>
  <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
  <wp:post_id>1012</wp:post_id>

<item>
  <title>It's The Firkin' Weekend Baby, I'm About To Have Me Some Fun.</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/04/02/its-the-firkin-weekend-baby-im-about-to-have-me-some-fun/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2015 08:12:07 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1027</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Over 30 Southern California breweries lugged over casks full of beer for theÂ second annual sold-out FirkFest, a festival of cask ale, two Saturdays ago (ha! I'm busy doing stuff, what I can I say?) hosted by the <a href="http://blog.ocbeerblog.com/">OC Beer Blog</a>. It took place at the cozy Farmer's Park, located right inÂ the ever-so-hipÂ <a href="http://anaheimpackingdistrict.com/">Packing District</a>Â of Anaheim.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/img_1390.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1033" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/img_1390.jpg" alt="Processed with VSCOcam with p5 preset" width="660" height="495" /></a>

It wasÂ only the second beer fest I've been to. Don't judge me, I like to sit and enjoy my beer and avoid crowds. This beer fest is in a league of its own. For one, it's a cask ale fest. Beer in casks, like the good ol' days. A method still popular in England.Â And two,Â IÂ got to help MisterÂ Nagel ofÂ the OC Beer Blog out and help pour beers for <a href="http://www.ballastpoint.com/">Ballast Point</a>!

Cask ales are unique in that you may never taste those exact flavors again because of the spontaneous fermentation process. It lets breweries have fun and twerk some of their crowd favorites or make a whole new beer specifically for this event.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/vscocam-photo-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1042" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/vscocam-photo-1.jpg" alt="Processed with VSCOcam with a5 preset" width="660" height="495" /></a>

Ballast Point brought with them a cask of Longfin Margarita Lager with key lime and sea salt 4.2% ABV and a Spicy Grapefruit Sculpin with habanero 7% ABV that was either a hit or miss with the crowd. Earlier in the day, the Sculpin gave off a grapefruit scent and start with a habanero finish, but later people commented on the fact that it smelled like sea water. I had some towards the end of the fest and that it did! Ballast Point really knows how to capture San Diego in a cask. I was a fan, except that it was the first beer I had after pouring and every beer I had after tasted like a habanero-infused <span style="text-decoration:underline;">insert beer name here</span>.

I enjoyed the Longfin margarita; it tasted like a mellowed-out margarita. Mellowed-out in the sense that you didn't get that kick from tequila!

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/goodluck.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1034" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/goodluck.jpg" alt="goodluck" width="600" height="402" /></a>

My most memorable beers: <a href="http://www.valiantbrewing.com/">Valiant's</a>Â Good Luck â a really thick Quantarium Barrel-Aged Stout with coffee, vanilla and licorice 16% ABV, but it tasted pretty good for a high alcohol percentage beerÂ and <a href="http://www.smogcitybrewing.com/">Smog City's</a> Pho-tastic â phoreakin' weird! It was made with thai basil, which is what gave the beer the pho taste, but phok. <a href="http://www.monkishbrewing.com/">Monkish</a>Â had a pleasant chamomile and lavender saison and Noble Ale Works had a really good Lebowski and Naughty Sauce baby Â of a milk stout that I'm starting to crave thinking about it.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/joeypour.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1035" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/joeypour.jpg" alt="joeypour" width="600" height="402" /></a>

There was also a first annual chili cook-off between OC Chefs. I have zero photos of chili, I was too busy eating and judging. Popular burger restaurant <a href="https://slaters5050.com/">Slaters 50/50</a> won with their All-American ground turkey, bacon chili that was on fritos and topped off with sour cream, but my favorite was from packing house native, Indian restaurantÂ <a href="http://adyaoc.com/#about-intro">Adya</a>, who put an Indian spin on chili and made it with lamb, black cardamom, bay leaf and 3 kinds of chiles. It was garnished with cilantro and full of so many bright and refreshing flavors.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/fourbrewers.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1036" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/04/fourbrewers.jpg" alt="fourbrewers" width="600" height="402" /></a>

Proceeds of this event went to <a href="http://inspireartisticminds.org/">Inspire ArtisticÂ Minds</a>, a nonprofit organizationÂ that helps fund those glorious souls that are in the food and beverage industries expand their knowledge in their field. For instance, bad ass brewers Evan Price and Brad Kominek of <a href="http://www.noblealeworks.com/">Noble Ale Works</a>Â were sent to England through IAM and made a damn good English Pale Ale at FirkFest to bring to the fest.

FirkFest will be returning next year with plans to double in its capacity, so buy your tickets before they sell out nextÂ time!]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>The Road to Zion</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/05/29/the-road-to-zion/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 29 May 2015 04:22:53 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1074</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>I ask her the question, âHow long do you have?â
And with no hesitation, she says, âOne week and a halfâ
I wonder, will she make it wherever she may go?
She listens as I say to her, âYou donât have to be aloneâ

Leaving LA, Tobias Jesso Jr.</blockquote>
I officially have one week and a half until I leave LA. Ever since I've heard this song, I've been anxious for the dayÂ I could say those words myself and mean it. It's just been this week that I could finally sit in bed and have no responsibilities except go to work at 3 in the afternoon, which means lots of time to sit and anticipate my trip this summer- backpack Europe!

Last week I took one last tripÂ and went camping at <a href="http://www.nps.gov/zion/index.htm">Zion National Park</a> in Utah. Take note and do not visit the park during Memorial Day weekend. It is the busiest time of year and if you're like me, you like going out to nature to escape the humans. Even thoughÂ just about every hiking trail was full of people, me and my friends did manage to find our own off beaten path on the Court of the Patriarchs stop. It was beautiful as we watched the sky go from blue to grey and blue again while the sun set.

We did attempt Angel's Landing, Zion's most popular hike, on the first day, but quickly got poured on our way up and bailed. This was the coldest, wettest camping trip yet.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0076_web.jpg">Â </a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0076_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1066 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0076_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0076_web" width="600" height="402" /></a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0076_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1069 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/andrew2.jpg" alt="andrew2" width="600" height="402" /></a>Â Â <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0033_web.jpg">Â </a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0033_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1063 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0033_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0033_web" width="600" height="402" /></a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0033_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1062 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0014_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0014_web" width="600" height="402" /></a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0140_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1067 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0140_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0140_web" width="600" height="402" /></a>Â <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0043_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1064 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/05/dsc_0043_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0043_web" width="600" height="402" /></a>]]></content:encoded>
