<item>
  <title>Ain't It GrandÂ </title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/03/leave-me-breathless-grand-canyon-national-park/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 03 Jun 2015 03:04:40 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1082</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Anxious to see&nbsp;the sunrise paint&nbsp;the canyon's walls, I desperately rushed over to find it just&nbsp;to have my breath stolen from me. If I were to describe the Grand Canyon in one word, it would be: breathtaking. It was a word I never understood until this cold morning.

I think I sat in different spots around the rim, watching the light fill the canyon for over an hour.

"This is what mornings should be like," was all I could think. In that moment, I was content and appreciative to witness nature's beauty.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0029_web.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1083 aligncenter" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0029_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0029_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0092_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1084 size-full" class="aligncenter wp-image-1085 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0101_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0101_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a alt="DSC_0125_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0133_web.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1087 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0133_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0133_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0172_web.jpg"><img <item>
  <title>So Long, West Coast</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/10/so-long-west-coast/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2015 05:41:17 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1098</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[The scent of Popeye's fried chicken fills the air on board the plane on my way to Baltimore to fulfill the ticket that started it all: a one-way ticket from Baltimore to Reykjavik for only $178. I'm wondering if I can barter some homemade shortbread cookies for a piece of that chicken.

The first leg of my trip began in Las Vegas, where I intended to highlight attractions outside of the strip like the Valley of Fire, but a phone call on my drive from California to Vegas changed it all. Heck, it almost changed this entire trip. My cousin called telling me my aunt passed away. Growing up in Hawai'i, everyone made us all so close.&nbsp;

Now There I was starting the very beginning of my trip, driving theough the desert to get my car to Vegas to spend the summer with my aunts while I traveled abroad. Now I was in the midst of the loss of a loved one, a woman who was strong and always made everyone laugh.&nbsp;

I struggled feeling like I needed to head back home to Hawai'i with everyone, but knowing the last conversation I had with my aunty was her saying how proud and happy she was for me to be going on this trip I was torn. In the end I decided that what would make me and my aunt happiest would be if I continued on because now my aunt could join me.&nbsp;

She said she wished she would've traveled more so I figured I could take her with me. There's an empty seat to my right and I just imagine her next to me, smiling.&nbsp;

Life takes everyone on different routes. Sometimes life gets taken too soon. For the first time in my life in January, I thought I was going to die. I hiked Mount Baldy and ended up holding on for my life trying to climb a mountain we saw to be our only way out after getting lost in unexpected climates.&nbsp;

A few months later I managed to somehow save a friend's life by accidentally dropping a box on her at work. I felt horrible. She went to the hospital just to be safe as advised by out district manager and as it turns out, she was anemic and had a red blood cell count so low that the doctors and nurses were in shock that she was standing there before their eyes.&nbsp;

We as people take life for granted as if there's always a tomorrow, but what if tomorrow never comes? If you died now, would you be satisfied by your accomplishments? Have you lived a fulfilling life?&nbsp;

These photos are from Mount Baldy. For a while it was hard for me to go through them after spending 12 hours trapped within the mountain and dancing with the Grim Reaper, but now it's a nice reminder that I am in control of my life. I'm pretty sure I got up the mountainside solely based on will power. I could have let go and that was the scariest thought, that I was in control. My buddy Christian wrote a song about the experience that sums it up perfectly-&nbsp;<a href="https://soundcloud.com/christian_young/up-is-the-only-way-down">Up Is The Only Way Down</a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0059_web.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1099" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0059_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0059_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0034_web.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1100" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0034_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0034_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0032_web.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1101" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0032_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0032_web" width="600" height="402"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0048_web.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1102" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0048_web.jpg" alt="DSC_0048_web" width="600" height="402"></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Biophilia</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/10/biophilia/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2015 20:00:49 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1107</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>Biophilia hypothesis: the idea that humans possess an innate tendency to seek connections with nature and other forms of life.</blockquote>
The cool breeze hits my face as it rustles the branches causing them to do a little subtle dance. I am surrounded by the sound of birds chirping and every so often, I'll catch a glimpse of them flying through the trees in my peripherals. It is a perfect day in Annapolis- 79 degrees, the sun is out, humidity is low.&nbsp;

I've been sitting outside in my friends backyard, which happens to be the woods, for hours now. The longer I sit here, the more I am reminded that my sense of home lies within the trees. I feel sheltered and guarded in its leafy walls like a child that hides behind their mother or father. I may have gotten a few mosquito bites while hanging out here, but for me it's worth it. Especially after coming from that desert heat.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3560.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3560.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
I am reading the <a href="http://www.ericweinerbooks.com/books/the-geography-of-bliss/description/">Geography of Bliss</a>.&nbsp;I realized that's what my trip this summer is really about, how people in other countries find happiness because I know my idea of happiness doesn't fit the American standards. America is about status, money, consumerism, all work and no play. Oftentimes there is no time to sit back and take in the little things.&nbsp;

Our food has been tainted that other countries will not accept our meat and produce. I'd like to live simply and eat food in it's pure form, not a fruit that may have genes of a fish or a chicken that has never seen daylight. At least craft beer is pure, maybe that's why I love it so much.

America has been growing disconnected from truly living, in my opinion at least, and I want to see what living is like across the sea.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3561.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3561.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

}";s:8:"response";a:2:{s:4:"code";i:401;s:7:"message";s:12:"Unauthorized";}s:7:"cookies";a:1:{i:0;O:14:"WP_Http_Cookie":5:{s:4:"name";s:4:"lidc";s:5:"value";s:79:""b=LB46:g=231:u=5:i=1433966466:t=1434001292:s=AQFqusLbfRQbDDzg00yhNGDmA5xR55Q2"";s:7:"expires";i:1434001292;s:4:"path";s:1:"/";s:6:"domain";s:13:".linkedin.com";}}s:8:"filename";N;}}}s:10:"error_data";a:0:{}}]]></wp:meta_value>
  </wp:postmeta>

<item>
  <title>Back in Iceland | Day 1</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/13/back-in-iceland/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 13 Jun 2015 12:00:35 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1125</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[After 5 years, I've made it back to the land of fire and ice. I sit in CafÃ© Mezzo finding myself in a weird juxtaposition looking at Nordic flags outside, but hearing bad country music coming from the speaker above me. I've traveled thousands of miles across the sea to the home of Sigur RÃ³s and BjÃ¶rk to listen to music I've avoided in the states.&nbsp;

Clear blue skies fill the country's capital, which I wandered for a couple of hours after my arrival. I caught the <a href="https://www.re.is/flybus/">Flybus</a>&nbsp;from KeflavÃ­k airport into ReykjavÃ­k, probably the best way to get to the city. It's a 45 minute ride, complete with free wifi, that allows you to see some of Iceland's extraterrestrial landscapes. You can get dropped off at your hotel or the&nbsp;<a href="http://www.bsi.is/index_en.html">BSI main bus station</a>&nbsp;and from there it's a short walk to the city. &nbsp;I don't know if people typically walk from there, but I spotted <a href="http://www.hallgrimskirkja.is/">HallgrÃ­mskirkja</a>&nbsp;and knew once I got there I could roam the city.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0005.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0005.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;

Fun fact: BSI is also home to FljÃ³tt og Gott ("Fast and Good") where you can find <a href="https://guidetoiceland.is/history-culture/the-worlds-most-disgusting-icelandic-food">sviÃ°- sheep's head</a>&nbsp;for your consumption. Being at the bus terminal brought back memories of one drunken night in ReykjavÃ­k, running into locals that bought shots of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brenniv%C3%ADn">BrennivÃ­n</a>&nbsp;who decided it was a great idea to feed the Americans sheep face. When in Rome, right? I was a pescetarian (ate seafood, no land animals) &nbsp;at the time and was haunted by images of the sheep's head the next day. All day. It didn't taste bad, but I'd choose drinking BrennivÃ­n over eating sviÃ° any day.&nbsp;

<img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0003.jpg" alt="">&nbsp;&nbsp;

Living in America, you forget cities still sleep. Here in Iceland and even Japan, being an early riser does you no good. Most shops or restaurants aren't open until 10 or 11. Until then, you can wander the empty streets and take in the scenery.&nbsp;

This whole backpacking Europe thing still hasn't sunk in. Being here just feels like I'm home. I think I was born on the wrong island in this life. It's the one place I've traveledto where I wondered why I had to leave. I've been curious with how my trip will be, starting in the place I didn't want to leave the first time around, but this country music is doing a good job in making me want to leave... this cafe at least. I'm just tired now from walking for hours and still fighting a cold, so in this cafe I linger.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0001.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0001.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0002.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0002.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0016.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/dsc_0016.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Iceland, you've changed | Day 2</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/17/iceland-youve-changed/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 17 Jun 2015 03:19:48 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1130</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I learned on the first day of this trip to expect the unexpected. It may be cliche, but it's true. I'm learning quickly how hard it is stay motivated when travelling while battling a cold that just doesn't seem to want to go away and maybe it's actually because of travelling that the cold isn't going away?

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0007.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0007.jpg" alt=""></a><span style="line-height:28px;">&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height:28px;">&nbsp;</span>
This trip to Iceland really gave me insight to life on the island through the eyes of a local. No matter where you live and how much your home is envied by others, you get used to it and it's just home. The beautiful landscapes just become another backdrop to your everyday life. Hawai'i is fantasized by many, but for me it's a been there, done that, there's a whole world to see sort of thing!
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0009.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0009.jpg" alt=""></a>
My favorite part about Iceland was being reunited with an old friend. I couchsurfed with her the last time I visited and she was kind enough to invite me for dinner with her family. I got to meet her parents, fiancÃ©, GarÃ°ar, and her cute 14-month-old daughter, FjÃ³la.&nbsp;

It was the first day of the year they could eat outside, their first summer day really. Her fiancÃ© made dinnerâ lobster and lamb. Score! Then they tell me how great it is to have a chef in the family. He works at the second best restaurant in ReykjavÃ­k. HELL YEAH! It's the best food I've ever had in Iceland and well, the best food I've had in a while since I've been trying to save money for this trip. I was never a fan of lamb, but this one won me over. It was so tender and juicy, like a really nice steak. Icelandic lamb is the sh*t!

After dinner, GarÃ°ar shared a bottle of some homebrew his friends made. I'd say it was a mellow IPA. Majority of the flavors were hops, a little citrusy, but also felt close to a saison to me. But heck, my senses haven't been the best since I've had my sinuses clogged up. That was followed up with some gin and tonic made by him. ÃsdÃ­s is lucky to have a chef that actually enjoys cooking at home too.&nbsp;
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3692.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3692.jpg" alt=""></a>
ÃsdÃ­s and I went downrown to<a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com/Restaurant_Review-g189970-d1852122-Reviews-Baejarins_Beztu_Pylsur-Reykjavik_Capital_Region.html"> the Laundromat Cafe</a>. A pretty hipster concept- restaurant upstairs and the only laundromat in town, downstairs. Drank one of Iceland's most popular beer <a href="http://www.beeradvocate.com/beer/profile/23680/61914/">BrÃ­Ã³</a> (if you don't count the piss beer), a pilsner so a pretty easy drink. I was tempted to have <a href="http://einstokbeer.com/">EinstÃ¶k</a>&nbsp;(the white ale seems like an Icelandic favorite), but I know we have it in the states so I pass. And what's better than to finish the night with <a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com/Restaurant_Review-g189970-d1852122-Reviews-Baejarins_Beztu_Pylsur-Reykjavik_Capital_Region.html">the best hot dog in Iceland</a>&nbsp;and your leftover beer (from the bar that closed while you were still drinking), at the harbor watching the midnight sun with an old friend.&nbsp;<span style="line-height:28px;">&nbsp;</span>
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3688.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3688.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;<span style="line-height:28px;">&nbsp;</span>

Iceland has changed since I've been there last, 5 years ago. A lot is geared towards tourists now, more construction, something I'm familiar with back home. The city may have lost a bit if it's charm. It lost a small venue I saw a show in to what will soon be a hotel. Hearing about these changes broke my heart, being surrounded by Americans while abroad shattered it even more, but Iceland will forever have a piece of my heart. I'm convinced I was born on the wrong island, but an island nonetheless, and I think that's what fascinates me the most. We have similar values, growing up on an island, but I come from an island full of 1.42 million people and their island is home to 323 thousand. I recommend you visit island soon before the tourist industry takes over.&nbsp;

Everyone in Iceland speaks English and it's a nice mix between America and England, as I learned on this trip. Afterall, it's tucked between the two continents. Burgers everywhere! But more nature than burgers.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3693.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3693.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>No</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/?p=1132</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 30 Nov -0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1132</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[In Norway, I'd find myself naturally on the lookout for police, security or any "authority" figure saying you can't be doing something, but it was always in my head. Like my friends skating on top of the tourist information building at Steindalsfossen, perfectly fine. In the states, you'd be guaranteed to be harassed by someone telling you skateboarding was not allowed. I hopped the fence near the waterfall to take a trail that led to the river that produced the waterfall. It was beautiful, but I also found myself in fear of someone questioning my actions and getting in trouble. Merica!

After doing my own exploring, I watch my friends skate with the sound of the waterfall and sheep bells behind. Constantly distracted by the sound of sheep <i>baa-ing</i>, I'm distracted by what I'd rather watch- my friend trying to skate a ledge or sheep grazing on grass. One thing's for sure, the light is hitting he picturesque landscape behind me perfectly. I keep wanting to take a picture each time I look at it, but I soak in the imagery myself. Ah, I love you Norway.&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Sognefjorden, Norway | Day 5</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/17/sognefjorden/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 17 Jun 2015 09:47:01 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/17/sognefjorden/</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Cameras are clicking away on this ferry ride and I'm just trying my best not to hurl. Part of being a good guest is keeping up with your hosts, even if that means drinking whiskey and coke until 5 in the morning when you know you have to wake up to catch a ferry at 8. Not a good mix to travel on water with.

The <a href="http://www.sognefjord.no/en/">Sognefjord</a> is the longest and deepest fjord in Norway. The fjords are what brought me to Bergen specifically, so I put on my big girl pants and forced myself out the door because today is my last day here. It is a 5 hour ferry ride that takes your through the fjord from Bergen to FlÃ¥m. I can't wait to get to the city and eat!

Norway reminds me a lot of Washington, except everything is bigger, for the trolls of course.&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3816.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_3816.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Midsummer in Sweden | Day 8</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/24/midsummer-in-sweden-day-8/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 24 Jun 2015 10:06:22 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1143</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[The Stockholm city life to the Swedish countryside is just a train ride away and to me, that's perfect. I wrote before I left the states that I was afraid that I'd fall madly in love with a city early on my trip and not want to go anywhere else. It happened. I sit here trying to visualize the rest of Europe to motivate me to go and in time I will carry on, but for now I presume I'll stay. I suppose I can see the bonfire going down the canal in Copenhagen for sankthansaften another year because I'm sure this will not be my last time in Scandinavia.&nbsp;

Midsummer in Sweden was my main goal for this trip and it was probably some of the best days of my life. It was nice to disappear into the countryside and just be surrounded by trees, music and food to celebrate the longest day of the year. I had schnapps chased with pickled herring, tradition for the occasion. I think chasing alcohol with the vitamin D, omega-3 fish is a great idea while drinking. &nbsp;

The weekend was filled with food, so much food! It made me feel like I was back home at one of my family gatherings with the overabundance of food and eating till you couldn't possibly eat more. My favorite dish was the fresh, homemade rhubarb pie made from rhubarb picked from their garden.&nbsp;

The actual midsummer day was dark, wet and rainy, but the rest of the weekend was full of sunshine and blue skies that I jumped into the Baltic Sea. Well, that was ice cold. And the boys disappeared off to the ice cream truck and came back with a box full of ice cream. Sweden is fine by me.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0029.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0029.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a <item>
  <title>Fall in love in/with Stockholm | Day 12</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/25/stuck-in-stockholm-day-11/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2015 14:18:38 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1186</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[I fell in love with Stockholm since I got to the airport and I spotted a pizza restaurant and a sushi restaurant in the corner of my eye as I tried to find the train station to get to the city. And when the the guy that worked for the train looked up directions for me to get to my hotel and even printed me a copy. I fell in love when I could sit on the subway and have some room to breathe. Not feeling rushed or like I'll get trampled over like I have in other cities. And when it went through the city and I spotted the unique architecture.&nbsp;

I fell in love when I got a hotel room for one night to regroup, listen to Angus and Julia stone and pretend I was in my apartment again. I fell in love with the city knowing I could walk from Japanese food to craft beer on tap. From what I've seen so far, the U.S. reigns the beer world although there are Swedish "piss beers" that are by far, better than all of ours. I fell in love at the supermarket when I saw it had a good variety of Asian AND Mexican food under one roof and cream cheese flavored chips.&nbsp;

I fell in love knowing I could escape to the forests in the countryside on a train ride. And when I learned about All Man's Right which means you can pick food and camp just about anywhere in the wild, as long as you're not invading someone's space. The land belongs to everyone, the way it should be. I fell in love walking though the city in the rain and with its cobblestone streets. I walked its streets often and am still as intrigued as I was when I first stepped foot on them.&nbsp;

I've been in Europe for nearly 2 weeks now. I've been hiding out in Sweden for a week. As far as I can recall, this is the longest I've visited any place in a while. I don't think I've gone anywhere in the past year and stayed for more than 5 days and here I am on a train to Copenhagen 3 days later than intended. I finally worked up the courage to leave.&nbsp;

I fell in love in/with Sweden, just not with salted licorice candy or having to pay to use a toilet, but that's easily forgiven with Moomin stuff everywhere.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0041.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0041.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;<span style="line-height:28px;">&nbsp;</span>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0040.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0040.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0039.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0039.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0038.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0038.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0037.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0037.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0036.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0036.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0035.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0035.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0034.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0034.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0033.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0033.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0030.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0030.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0031.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_0031.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;

<item>
  <title>Train of thought: thoughts from a train</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/25/train-of-thought-thoughts-from-a-train/</link>
  <pubDate>Thu, 25 Jun 2015 16:32:58 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1214</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<ol>
	<li>I want a burger and fries from <a href="http://www.in-n-out.com/mobile/">In-N-Out</a></li>
	<li>I should've packed food for this 5-hour train ride&nbsp;</li>
	<li>&nbsp;I'm still in love with Sweden, especially on this train ride. It's beautiful.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Maybe I'll get a home in the countryside</li>
	<li>I don't miss America. I don't want to go back.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Is this guy next to me lonely? <i>I just want you to look at me</i>&nbsp;<i>and see that I'm good enough&nbsp;</i>has been on repeat and blasting from his headphones for a while now</li>
	<li>I'm getting bored. 2 more hours...</li>
	<li>Where's the bridge to Denmark?</li>
	<li>Where are all my friends to talk to?</li>
	<li>I'm hungry...</li>
	<li>Trains &gt; Airplanes</li>
	<li>Where am I now? This city looks full&nbsp;</li>
	<li>There's a kid waving at the train</li>
	<li>I think I'm ready to get to Italy. &nbsp;</li>
	<li>I wonder what the rest of my trip will be like.</li>
</ol>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>When in Denmark | Day 14</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/27/when-in-denmark-day-14/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 27 Jun 2015 15:18:42 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1221</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Do as the Danish do. I've only been in Denmark for a little over 24 hours, but I've already seen so much.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4109.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4109.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Took a walk to the beach where you can find the Nordic food lab used for NOMA, the world's best restaurant, and Sweden across the sea. I learned that when you graduate high school here you get a party truck with your friends and it stops at each parents house with booze and food waiting for you. Saw boys jump into the canal, naked.&nbsp;

&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4158.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4158.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Strolled through Christiania, a hippy commune that started in the 60s that's exempt from the EU that lies right in the middle of Copenhagen. I've never seen so many people rolling joints in my life. It's nice to see a place where everyone lives so freely, but there is a weird contrast in the Green Light District where people who don't live there who are probably gangsters sell weed. Other than that, it's a nice community.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4157.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4157.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Copenhagen rules in street food. There's a pier full of them, but since I already ate sushi, I got rhubarb juice instead and sat on the dock, watching people go pass drinking on boats and kayaking. Got to see NOMA, the beehives they keep outside for their honey, and daydream about eating in there one day.&nbsp;

&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4159.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4159.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;

Went to the harbor to find more street food with a DJ. Had a bagel sandwich and some beers. Saw the guy from Aqua who says <i>Come on Barbie, let's go party </i>who now has a food cart after winning Master Chef. The most famous&nbsp;Danish porn star was at his side making burgers. Ninja Warrior was started being filmed once it was over.&nbsp;

&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4160.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4160.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Now I've managed to get myself to <a href="http://www.roskilde-festival.dk/">Roskilde festival</a>, one of Europe's biggest music festival, for free by volunteering to work 4 shifts. I'll be here all week. And now I just got into a debate about the Game of Thrones finale while in the visitors lounge and being told about a Game of Thrones party at one of the campsites tomorrow. Hello Denmark.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4161.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4161.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4156.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4156.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Roskilde Festival, What Day Is it? | Day 17</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/06/30/roskilde-festival-what-day-is-it-day-17/</link>
  <pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2015 09:38:21 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1238</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Tents everywhere, people everywhere, music everywhere, beer everywhere, piss everywhere. The music hasn't even begun and won't begin for 2 more days, yet the fields of Roskilde have been full of people since Saturday. Today is Tuesday.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4204.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4204.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Roskilde Festival's gates opened at 4 p.m. Saturday and it's a sight to be seen. Once the gates open, people run through like wildebeests in the Lion King to get themselves a camp spot. Each time someone ran past the spectators at the fence, they received cheers and applause from the audience.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4208.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4208.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
People live freely and primitively during the week long festival and the idea of a shower and soap start to become foreign to you. Many get creative with their food; I spotted someone ready to eat lunch with their bottle of sriracha and can of baked beans. There are places to get food too, pretty good and decently priced, but I'm looking forward to the street food that'll open up once the music starts at the fest.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4207.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4207.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Me? I just showed up, hesitant to work, but it gets you free wristband into the music festival that features Paul McCartney. Seeing a Beatle for free? Why not. I'm looking forward to seeing Father John Misty and First Aid Kit.&nbsp;

I'm spending so much time in Scandinavia, I'm beginning to think I am one. I just really need to learn the language, even though everyone speaks English. These countries are more easygoing than I'm used to and I'm quite envious that I didn't grow up here. Kids start going to this festival since they were 16 and parents seem to have more trust in their children here.&nbsp;

Everyday I'm in disbelief that I am here at the festival, in Denmark, in Europe, so far from my hometown. People I've been meeting are in disbelief that I just got to this country and now I'm at this festival. Everyday on this trip so far, I look around and ask myself <i>what the heck am I doing here?! </i>With no regrets and no desire to go back to America. These places are living right.&nbsp;

Sorry for the lack of photos. I've been too involved observing everything through my own eyes.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4209.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/06/img_4209.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Goodbye Copenhagen | Day 24</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/07/10/goodbye-copenhagen-day-24/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 10 Jul 2015 12:34:13 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1246</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[When people think of the happiest place on earth, I think for many Americans, Disneyland comes to mind. Denmark has been named the happiest country in the world and well the land of Mickey Mouse can't come close (for me). It was hard to leave Scandinavia when it's countries all rank in the top 10 happiest countries in the world.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1252" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image1.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="443" /></a>

The more I learned about the culture, the more I couldn't understand the American life. Nothing ever seemed logic to me in the U.S., and there I was in Denmark convinced that I was born in the wrong part of the world. Would it be so hard to use this country as an example on how to take care of its people? Oh, but it would go against everything America is about. The Scandinavian way of life just well, wouldn't be American.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1253 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image2.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="443" /></a>

When a school banned soda and junk food to keep the American youth healthy, parents fought it. In Denmark, it's not found in schools and unhealthy items are more costly, causing people to eat better. Back home, it would cost me maybe 3 bucks for a bundle of asparagus, but I could get 2 tacos for 99 cents. Why is obesity a problem in America? It's cheaper to eat bad.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image3.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1254" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image3.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="496" /></a>

It is free to attend a university in Denmark and students receive a nice allowance while studying. Meanwhile students in America, including myself, are racking up a large debt in student loans and working at the same time, struggling to get by. This allowance is so good that they are able to travel and broaden their world views. People receive vacation time and therefore are able to strengthen relationships with family and friends, while in America we can neverÂ find the time.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image4.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1256" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image4.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="495" /></a>

At Roskilde festival, there were so many times I thought to myself that I should write, but I found myself too involved in observing what seemed like a free world, an extension of Christiania. Sure everyone was peeing everywhere, but everyone also got along in one large-scale community. I witnessed smple acts of kindness that put me in awe because I live in America, like water being handed out to festival goers and a cart being pushed around offering people sunscreen. What is this place?

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image5.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1257" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image5.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="495" /></a>

And if you're wondering, Roskilde Festival was amazing. Organic beer, lots of diverse food everywhere, a food court full of 75 percent organic food, good music, but it is not recommended for the clean freak, germaphobe type. You smell piss everywhere, lots of piss, porta potties become the norm and what's a shower?

But yes, America is not a bad place to live, we could just take way better care of our people.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>How's Berlin? | Day 26</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/07/10/hows-berlin-day-26/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 10 Jul 2015 18:17:44 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1247</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Arriving half-asleep in a city you've never been, dropped off in a bus terminal that looks like you could be anywhere in the world when all you can envision in your head is a Berlin Wall covered in graffiti that is nowhere in sight might cause some people to panic. Where is the city? I arrived in Berlin at almost 7 a.m. after an 8 hour bus ride full of sleeping on and off, having to wake up randomly because everyone's getting off the bus and after roaming a bit, without the slightest clue where you are and what's going on, you realize you're trapped because somehow you're now on a ferry. Now that freaked me out. Just a little...

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image6.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1264" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image6.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="443" /></a>

Since I arrived in Berlin so early, I knew I could afford to waste time so I bought an all-day ticket valid in all zones for the subway and hopped on, hoping I'd pass an area that looked like the heart of the city. It never happened. Two hours later I somehow managed to get myself to the Brandenburg Gate. Brandenburg, the only word on the subway map that meant anything. Luckily, a Starbucks is located right in front of the tourist destination full of good ol' wifi so I didn't have to feel so lost and alone, if only for 25 minutes. To my luck, I discovered a free tour that started right in that very spot. There I was, me and my blue 65 liter backpack learning the history of Berlin on a walking tour.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image7.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1265" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image7.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="440" /></a>

I learned that Berlin was ahead of its time and strived for equality prior to the tragic history everyone knows, saw the balcony that Michael Jackson dangled his baby and where Hitler committed suicide, as well as the last Nazi building in the world and the location where book burning took place. The highlight was making a friend with a girl from the Philippines while on the tour, who is also traveling alone. I decided to cut my northern Germany time even shorter so that I could meet her in Prague and hopefully we'll be able to meet in Munich too. It's nice how things work out and sometimes traveling alone isn't so bad when lone wolves seek out other lone wolves.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image10.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1268" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image10.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="443" /></a>

I'm actually in Leipzig now, a city chosen strictly for beer purposes, and I'm impressed. It is a beautiful, small city. The city just turned 1000 this year. After seeing buildings that looked old, but we're actually new in Berlin (90 percent of buildings are new thanks to WW2), I was ready to see authentic old buildings. Although Berlin may not be full of beautiful architecture, it is full of subcultures and probably the best nightlife for the young and thriving. There was a random party under a bridge and another at the train station, compete with a DJ.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image8.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1266" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image8.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="443" /></a><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image9.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1267" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image9.jpg?w=660" alt="image" width="660" height="443" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Lost in Leipzig | Day 27</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/07/10/i-lost-in-leipzig-day-27/</link>
  <pubDate>Fri, 10 Jul 2015 22:49:02 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1271</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Leipzig is a little town south of Berlin that is full of hidden treasures like my favorite beer, the only reason I ended up here (I'll get to the beer traveling posts eventually). I started the day with a Polish family and a German friend by using <a href="https://m.blablacar.com/">BlaBlaCar</a>&nbsp;from Berlin to Leipzig,&nbsp;met a friend as soon as I got into the city that I was supposed to couchsurf with, then was faced with A LOT of alone time being lost. So much time, that I started being upset with myself for having the bright idea of backpacking Europe by myself for 2 months. &nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4397.jpg"><img width="2389" height="1602" alt="" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4397.jpg" title="" class="size-custom"></a>&nbsp;

Although I've been traveling alone for nearly a month now, I've had friends in all the places I've been up until this point. Sure, they were people I met for the first time, but with that one friend came a whole group of friends. There were two occasions during Roskilde festival that a teenage boy asked me, "Why are you alone?" that made me actually think about being alone, but then I knew my friends were around just not with me that very second. Here in Leipzig, I am alone.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4400.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4400.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;

On the car ride there, I brought up&nbsp;<a href="http://m.imdb.com/title/tt0758758/">Into the Wild</a>&nbsp;when discussing hitchhiking. I told him that when that movie ended I was upset that as a woman, I could never do that. He asked if that's what I took from the movie because he saw that the whole point of it was what Chris McCandless wrote at the very end- Happiness only real when shared.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4401-0.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4401-0.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;

I agreed. It's a thought that runs through my head very often. It's the very reason I was arguing with myself for deciding to backpack Europe for the summer, alone. By the end of the night I felt so desperate for friends that I almost asked strangers on the street on my way to the brewery, if they wanted to join me for dinner and beer. But the truth is, it's not so bad being alone.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4399.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4399.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;

I think yesterday the combo of being lost for hours combined with no wifi and therefore no access to friends got the best of me. I walked for such a long time that I managed to come up with a few song ideas and write and it's because I have all this time to myself. Things I haven't been doing much of since I've had the company of friends. There's always pros and cons.&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4396-2.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4396-2.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
Leipzig itself is a charming old city. In the few hours I did have a friend, I was shown the coolest things: panoramic view of the city, a bar within old city walls that college students dug up, the Spoon family- the last neon sign left in the city from the factory days of East Germany, and what used to be the only train station to get to Bavaria that is now a brewery to my favorite beer style (Gose).

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4402-0.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4402-0.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;
I spent today relaxing after spending the last 3 days walking for hours and hours. The highlight of my day has to be the sweet, juicy, finger-staining strawberries I got for just 1 euro which is about $1.11. I also finally got some currywurst! And I saw a man levitate? Still trying to figure out that sorcery. Just got to Prague. I've got to live that rock star life of being in a different city every night since I extended my stay in Scandinavia.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4403-0.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4403-0.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4404.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4404.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Czech Yourself | Day 29</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/07/19/czech-yourself-day-29/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 19 Jul 2015 19:50:11 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1291</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[With its attention to detail in its intricate architecture, Prague has got to be one of the most beautiful cities I've been to yet, but it also reminded me how much I miss forests and that sense of solitude. By the end of this bus ride (Munich to Innsbruck), I will have been in 6 cities and 3 countries in 7 days. This jet-set life has been both exciting and exhausting, but I've no desire to stay any longer. Backpacking all these cities has been like the dating, spending time in cities I know are not The One and I just want to keep moving on because why bother. Maybe you're thinking, "Well, you haven't spent much time in these cities." I guess I believe in love at first sight, don't walk by again.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image11.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1293" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image11.jpg" alt="image" width="648" height="434"></a>

Berlin, Leipzig, Prague, Pilsen and Munich are all great cities. They're cities that would have been nice to have a group of friends with to experience the night life. I was fortunate enough to have a group of friends in&nbsp;Pilsen, also met off couchsurfing, but unfortunately due to my "when in Rome" attitude, I tried steak tartare for the first time and my body hates me for it. Filling your belly with beer, raw beef and egg hinders you from going on what should have been a beer tour of the city. Nice one, Jante.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4660.jpg"><img class="size-custom aligncenter" title="" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4660.jpg" alt="" width="581" height="436"></a>&nbsp;Prague is truly a beautiful city, but it is so full of tourists. My favorite part was when I wandered through a park. Realizing there was a John Lennon Wall and it was nearby, I sought it. While doing so, I saw a dog that I watched it walk around for a bit. Seeing pets have been putting a smile on my face lately. Then I spotted the owner, an old man smiling at me as he also watched his dog whom I assumed didn't speak English. I smiled back and continued on. I looked on my map one last time trying to find this wall, when suddenly I hear a voice behind me with a Czech accent, "Lennon Wall?" I turn around and there was the old man. Somehow he knew exactly what I was looking for. He was able to give me very basic directions- right cornersky, right cornersky, left cornersky.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image12.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1297" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image12.jpg" alt="image" width="648" height="434"></a>

Down the street from the Lennon wall, you'll find the John Lennon Bar. I found a room left unoccupied, ordered myself a beer and enjoyed the songs of the Beatles. The room's acoustics were prime. I roamed the city for a while and eventually found myself lured to a riverside outdoor restaurant that held views of the castle and the Charles Bridge after seeing a girl enjoying a beer on a small dock. I finished my beer and was waiting for another one. In this time, fireworks went off behind me and the man playing classic rock songs on acoustic sang the words of Pink Floyd, "How I wish, wish you were here." I finished my night on that dock with my beer, enjoying the picturesque view seen in Prague's postcards. That night was the most content I have been being alone on this entire trip and grateful that to be there. Although I was content being alone, I was happy to know I'd have friends in Pilsen the next day.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image13.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1298" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image13.jpg" alt="image" width="648" height="434"></a>

Prague was full of beer, weird statues and cool bars and Pilsen wasn't any different. As I said earlier, I was a complete failure in Pilsen, sick from ingesting nothing but raw meat and beer. I did meet great people and one with the tragic love story. I was taken on a tour of a brewery and then later to a really cool, old western-themed bar. It would've been nice to be in Pilsen longer to actually enjoy it and not spend it recovering from poor decisions.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image14.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1299" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image14.jpg" alt="image" width="643" height="431"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image15.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1300" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image15.jpg?w=606" alt="image" width="606" height="406"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image16.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1301" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image16.jpg?w=639" alt="image" width="639" height="428"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image17.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1302" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image17.jpg?w=648" alt="image" width="648" height="434"></a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image18.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1303" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image18.jpg?w=641" alt="image" width="641" height="429"></a>&nbsp;

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4661.jpg"><img src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/img_4661.jpg" alt=""></a>&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>My Future Self in Munich | Day  32</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/07/22/my-future-self-in-munich-day-32/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 22 Jul 2015 11:03:49 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1308</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[There she was, sitting all alone in the largest beer garden in the world, licking her fingers with only a glass of beer and food to keep her company. I watched an old lady having lunch by herself in Hirschgarten, realizing she was mirroring me. I laughed to myself thinking, there's my future self: forever alone with just beer and food, going home to a cat or two or three. That just might be me.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image20.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1310" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image20.jpg" alt="image" width="634" height="476" /></a>
I passed on going to Neuschwanstein, the castle Cinderella's was modeled after, to spend a lazy Tuesday in Munich. I arrived just the day prior, met the Filipino girl I met in Berlin who acquired another female lone backpacker and immediately went to Dachau to check out the concentration camp. I don't think I ever want to go to another one in my lifetime; once is enough. How can humans be so cruel especially to each other? I just hope and pray to every higher power that there will never be another time like that, then I worry about what's going on in Africa and the Middle East.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image21.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1311" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image21.jpg" alt="image" width="644" height="484" /></a>
To bring our moods up, I tagged along on a beer tour this new friend was going on, another beer fan, another American, except from Michigan. Edelstoff, Dunkel, Weissebier, beer beer and beer. Unfortunately we both booked hostels outside of he city and it was getting late so we left the tour before we ever got our last beer and shot of JÃ¤ger.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image22.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1312" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image22.jpg" alt="image" width="648" height="487" /></a>
After hours of trial and error, I arrived to my hostel at almost 2 in the morning. I just had to book a hostel in the forest. The nice part about arriving late was that the Australian man at the reception/bar was eager to show me the future of the hostel- they invested in a little brewing machine so they will be the first hostel brewing beer.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image23.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1313" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/image23.jpg" alt="image" width="639" height="480" /></a>
Ah Munich. Honestly, I was eager to leave. I think I'd like to return to German cities with friends and just go out drinking. The beer taste real clean and fresh thanks to the German Beer Purity Law. But after so much time spent in cities full of tourists, I couldn't wait to get to a mountain.]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>In Innsbruck | Day 33</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/08/16/in-innsbruck-day-33/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 16 Aug 2015 23:58:36 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1318</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[An old city engulfed by mountains, full of athletic types, that's what Innsbruck is. What a breather it was to make a stop in Austria. Minimal tourists and mountains to look at in every corner. I was there for nature and wanted to see more than there was time for, but I took a hike up the mountain and that's all that matters. You can take a short bus ride to a mountain which makes things really convenient. It is gorgeous once you start hiking up and there seemed to be more mountain bikers than hikers. There are huts throughout the mountain too to fill your belly whenever you desire. It was literally a breath of fresh air after quickly going through cities.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/vscocam-photo-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1325" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/vscocam-photo-1.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="495" /></a>

That night there was a DJ that played by the river in front of the university library, filled with 20-something-year-olds drinking mostly beer. It ended at 10 p.m. and it was like the clock striking midnight for Cinderella, the reality of Innsbruck hit me. A girl born and raised there mentioned how you don't really get to see sunsets because of all the mountains. What?! A life without sunsets?! And when I drink, I get hungry, really hungry and found there was nowhere to get food. Even though it was only 10, the city is small enough that places close early. I hate this place. What is this life? Thank goodness I've been on a chip-binge since I got to Europe and snagged some Brazil do Salsa flavored chips on a grocery-run earlier in the day. Something to tie me over.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/vscocam-photo-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1326" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/vscocam-photo-2.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="495" /></a>

InnsbruckÂ is a great place to be immersed into the walls of nature, but to my disappointment, it is not a great place for late-night food.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/img_0125.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1327 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/img_0125.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/img_0130.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1328 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/img_0130.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/img_0131.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1329 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/img_0131.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="442" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/vscocam-photo-3.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1330 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/vscocam-photo-3.jpg?w=660" alt="" width="660" height="495" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Swiss Dreams | Day 37</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/09/01/swiss-dreams-day-37/</link>
  <pubDate>Tue, 01 Sep 2015 04:54:25 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1321</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p class="p1"><span class="s1">A road trip in an old Volkswagen van with classic rock coming from the stereo; I was livin' the dream. Growing up, I would watch Almost Famous and That 70's Show full of envy that I was not born in that era. I always longed for the day I could own a VW vanÂ and travel. Luckily,Â <a href="https://www.couchsurfing.com/">Couchsurfing</a> allowed me to cross paths with the coolest 22-year-old Swiss boy I know, Jannik. </span></p>
<p class="p1"><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-2-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1337" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-2-2.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a></p>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">I quickly traded the view of Lake Zurich to spend 3 hoursÂ road tripping down in his vanÂ to head south to Ticino. Ah, finally! I never thought the day that I'd get to live out my teenage fantasy would be in Switzerland. There I was, sun on my face, wind in my hair in the passenger seat, filled with the excitement ofÂ a little girl.</span></p>
<p class="p1"><a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-3-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1338" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-3-2.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="318" /></a></p>
Knowing that I was dying to be submerged intoÂ mother nature's arms, Jannik had the best idea for a detour to avoid trafficâ driving over the mountain instead of through it. That idea left us witness to land illustrated inÂ fairy tales. We found ourselves making a bouquet out of the furry flowers, surrounded byÂ marshmallow clouds.

StargazingÂ upon rocks in the shallowÂ river. Short hike into a little oasis. Singing and ukulele-playing under the tent during night rain. Walking around with aÂ watermelon. Swimming amongst mountainous backdrops. These were some of my most memorable daysÂ and perhaps why I took a long hiatus before finally writing this. Life was so simple, yet more fulfilling than ever. This was living.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1339 size-large" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-1.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="356" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-1-31.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1350" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-1-31.jpg?w=474" alt="" width="474" height="356" /></a>

[caption id="attachment_1341" align="alignnone" width="474"]<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-3.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-1341" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-3.jpg?w=474" alt="Processed with VSCOcam with hb2 preset" width="474" height="356" /></a> <img class="size-large wp-image-1343" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-4.jpg?w=474" alt="Processed with VSCOcam with hb2 preset" width="474" height="356" />[/caption]

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-5.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-1344" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/vscocam-photo-5.jpg?w=474" alt="Processed with VSCOcam with hb2 preset" width="474" height="356" /></a>
<p class="p1"></p>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>I'll Melt With You in Florence | Day 39</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/10/14/ill-melt-with-you-in-florence-day-39/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 14 Oct 2015 01:16:01 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1365</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Memorized by all the details on theÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florence_Cathedral">Cattedrale di Santa Maria del Fiore</a>, the main Cathedral of Florence, I asked my new friend if I could touch it. I couldn't wrap my head around the fact that people who lived hundreds of years ago created such beauty that could withstand time and it was there right in front of me. To graze my hands over the grooves of the building had me feeling like I was now a part of history.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0004-copywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1371" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0004-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0004-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

Florence is so rich with culture and the contrast of the city by day and by night is just that, day and night. The day is full of tourists and unbearable heat, but thanks to the tourists and unbearable heat, I found myself in line at an organic gelato shop that even made their own conesâ <a href="http://www.edoardobio.it/">Edoardo il Gelato Biologico</a>. After studying the menu intently while I eavesdropped other Americans discussing the weather, I chose vegan almond and decided to try Chianti, mostly out of curiosity and because my Florence native friend said it was his favorite red wine. The Chianti gelato was sweet and wine-y, of course! Delicious, especially since it was wine in gelato form. My biggest battle was eating it before it melted all over my hand.

Another day consisted of me strolling through the Lorenzo Street Market to get lunch. I got there late, so the food shops in Central Market were almost all closed. The important thing is that I managed to get myself a prosciutto sandwich with tomato and mozzarella, my favorite. Walked through the market and and was seduced by all the other food, but there I stood already with my sandwich in hand, admiring pastas of all shapes and sizes. This is where having a travel buddy could have been handy; we could've dispersed the collection of food for a joint feast. It's okay, I acquired prosciutto.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/prosciuttowp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1376" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/prosciuttowp.jpg" alt="prosciuttowp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

I also took my friend's suggestion at trying out <a href="http://www.laprosciutteria.com/eng_index.html">La Prosciutteria</a> when he found out my deep, deep love for prosciutto. They make sandwiches to order and have prosciutto EVERYWHERE! Slabs of prosciutto hung from the ceiling and if there were craft beer there, I may have thought I died and went to my idea of heaven. I asked the woman who slung sandwiches what she suggested and ended up with a prosciutto sandwich with a truffle spread. Truffle has a very heavy flavor, so I would keep that in my the next time I go around ordering truffle anything. The prosciuttoâ so salty, so flavorful, so tender, so perfect (<a href="http://janteziarra.com/2014/04/26/prosciutto-on-my-mind/">I love prosciutto</a>).

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0005-copywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1372" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0005-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0005-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

By night, my friend would give me a tour of all the different landmarks- from the <a href="http://piazza-signoria.com/">Piazza della Signoria</a>, home to the "Old Palace," or what I like to call "The Castle," and the open-air sculpture gallery to the <a href="http://www.visitflorence.com/florence-monuments/piazzale-michelangelo.html">Piazzale Michelangelo</a> to get a panoramic view of the city. We got wood-fired pizza that contained three different combinations, all involving cured meat, and got to order local craft beer. He even took me to a bar called <a href="http://www.yelp.com/biz/the-box-firenze">The Box</a> with the best cocktail I ever hadâ fresh watermelon with ginâ that seemed to play all my favorite musicians! All was so peaceful and calming and even charming at night, when compared to seeing exploring the city in the day.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/watermelonwp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1378" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/watermelonwp.jpg" alt="watermelonwp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

I could be in love with Florence with it's history of great artists like Michelangelo and Raphael or it's random Audrey Hepburn eyes graffiti and <a href="http://www.simonedauria.com/it/home-page">Simone DâAuria</a>'s "I Eat Earth" art installation of spoons. Heck, this wine-heavy city even has a craft beer scene. If it wasn't for the deathly heat and the infinite amount of stealthy mosquitoes that seemed to have a strong thirst for this foreigners blood, I might have been in love. And that was only the beginning...

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0002-copywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1370" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0002-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0002-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0014-copywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1375" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0014-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0014-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/audreywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1380" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/audreywp.jpg" alt="audreywp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0011-copywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1374" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0011-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0011-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/spoonwp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1377" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/spoonwp.jpg" alt="spoonwp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0006-copywp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1373" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/dsc_0006-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0006-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/castlewp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1379" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/castlewp.jpg" alt="castlewp" width="600" height="450" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Romanticized Rome | Day 41</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/11/09/romanticized-rome/</link>
  <pubDate>Mon, 09 Nov 2015 04:57:00 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1396</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[In these ruins, you are bound to find beauty. In this city, you will be amongst many other outsiders, tourists, and vendors trying to force a selfie stick purchase upon you. Rome was the only city on my trip I intended to play tourist and made a goal to see the Colosseum. I had been warned to maybe avoid Rome, especially this time of year due to Â the crowds, but I did it anyway.

Rome seems to be a city of romance, but in the summer heat, it was everything but romantic. Rome was the only city I thought to myself, "You stupid American tourist; you just walked yourself straight into a trap," after getting into what I thought was a cab, only to find no indication of it being a cab and a woman texting on her phone in the passenger seat. When I asked to get out, she assured me, "If you think we're going to do something bad, we're not." Yeah, <em>sure</em>. The cab driver, who seemed friendly at first, now hustled me for money after causing him to lose "clients." And after I finally got out of the cab, was called a bitch, which I replied with a thank you.

I found that public transportation shuts down early, which I couldn't understand. After visiting major cities like Tokyo and New York, I guess I just sort of assumed subways ran all night in major cities. A bus that never came and a closed subway line wasÂ the reason why I ended up in that cab. I will say though, the cab driver I got after resorting back to the cab after a shuttle to the airport I finally settled on failed to start, was nice.

But Rome, oh Rome, you are not for me. How I love your ruins and your art. Imagining a whole empire once thrived within this city and its ruins that still remain after all these years, leaves a person in awe. However, exploring the ruins in the heat required survival skills that consisted of seeking water fountains and constantly refillingÂ water bottles to avoid a heatstroke.

The art school drop-out and <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0367279/">Arrested Development</a> fan in me was so excited to see Michelangelo's <em><a href="http://www.italianrenaissance.org/michelangelo-creation-of-adam/">The Creation of Adam</a>Â </em>in the <a href="http://mv.vatican.va/3_EN/pages/CSN/CSN_Main.html">Sistine Chapel</a>. The art school drop-out me could spend all day marveling over all the art in Vatican City. Rome holds many beautiful things, yes, but Rome as a whole was just not for me.Â <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0052-copywp.jpg">
</a> <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0050wp.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1410 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0050wp.jpg" alt="DSC_0050wp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0031-copywp.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-1407 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0031-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0031-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0025-copywp.jpg"><img class="wp-image-1406 size-full aligncenter" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0025-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0025-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0016-copywp.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1408 aligncenter" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0016-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0016-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0021-copywp.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-1405 aligncenter" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/dsc_0021-copywp.jpg" alt="DSC_0021-copywp" width="600" height="402" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

<item>
  <title>Cinque Terre | Day 43</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/12/13/cinque-terre-day-43/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 13 Dec 2015 07:18:29 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1398</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[Ever since I left the Scandinavian islands and made my way inland through Europe, I was anxious to get to a coastal city againâ Cinque Terre, the five towns that sit alongside the cliffs offÂ the coast in Italy. The salt-filled wind brushed against my skin; I made it. I finally made it from the Baltic to the Mediterranean. After the hustle and bustle of the Italian city life, being on the beach was a nice breather.

I found a spot to camp in Deiva Marina, 15 minutes from Cinque Terre National Park by train. It was more like glamping since the campsite,Â <a href="http://www.campinglasfinge.com/en/">Camping La Sfinge</a>,Â provided tents complete with a bed:Â there were even showers and toilets!Â I could not wait to get the ocean after spending a lot of time in cities under the blazing sun. After checking in at the campsite and fighting millions of mosquitoes along the way, wine and prosciutto was obtained for a drunken walk to the beach. The Mediterranean is just a walk away from the train station, where you can find a handful of restaurants. The sun was setting by the time we arrived at the beach, but that didn't prevent us from jumping in. To my surprise, the ocean was as warm as bath water. I was content in the water, finally feeling free from the restraints of being inland. It was then that I truly realized that growing up on an island affected me; I needed to know that the shore was near.

Ah, it was that night that I discovered Trofie al Pesto. One word: pesto. This pasta resembled long-grained rice or worms a covered in pesto, one of my favorite things toÂ drench my mouth with. Which reminds me, I must find this at a restaurant near me becauseÂ it was THAT good.

Cinque Terre is not a place to escape the crowds. They're here too, especially while waiting for trains to get between the five towns. I only explored one. It wasn't until I tookÂ a detour away from the beach and into the buildings, I finally got to have that taste of Italy I imaginedâ laundry hanging on clotheslines, a good hole-in-the-wall food joint, sitting outdoors, taking as long as possible to finish a small cup of espresso.

[gallery type="rectangular" ids="1456,1455,1454,1453,1452,1451,1450,1449,1448,1447,1446" orderby="rand"]]]></content:encoded>
