<item>
  <title>Because I Cannes | Day 44</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/12/16/because-i-cannes-day-44/</link>
  <pubDate>Wed, 16 Dec 2015 15:34:21 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1400</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[After a week of unbearable heat and a plethora of mosquitoes bites on my body, an unwanted souvenir I acquired during my week in Italy, I was desperate to get to France. The trip there did not come easy.Â Failed plans of a rideshare created a day of traveling by train from Monterosso to Cannes on the most uncomfortable train ride yet. There was no air conditioning and at some point,Â no seats on the longest leg of the commute. No food either. It seemed that the universe wanted toÂ give me more reasons to want to get out of Italy more than I already wanted to. The South of France became my salvation. When the train finallyÂ left the Italian border, I was relieved. Even though Italy and France are right next to each other, I felt a huge difference in the air. We passed Nice and Antibes, until finallyâ Cannes.

I've heard that the French are rude, but I've only ever come across the nicest people. Here in Cannes, I booked an <a href="https://www.airbnb.com">AirBnb</a> with <a href="https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/1540597">Eric and Jonas</a>. I fell in love with them while reading reviews and fell in love even more when I met them.Â Their home is walking distance to the beach and near a cute farmer's market where I found a variety of homemade salami.Â Cannes reminded me of being back home in Hawai'i, particularly in Waikiki with the sidewalks full of tourist along the beach and high-fashioned shops right across. The concept seemed official when I came across a spot called "Waikiki" as if the universe sent a sign that it agreed. The ocean here, unlike Italy which felt like a bath, cooled you off in the heat. Everyone here seemed refreshed, rejuvenated and well, happy. I hung out on the beach drinking cheap wine and I, too, was happy.

If I were rich, I'd place a vacation home in this city and spend my days writing on the beach.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5027-copywp.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-1483"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1483" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5027-copywp.jpg" alt="IMG_5027-copywp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5062-copywp.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-1487"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1487" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5062-copywp.jpg" alt="IMG_5062-copywp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5091-copywp1.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-1489"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1489" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5091-copywp1.jpg" alt="IMG_5091-copywp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5057-copywp.jpg" rel="attachment wp-att-1486"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1486" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/img_5057-copywp.jpg" alt="IMG_5057-copywp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

&nbsp;

<item>
  <title>Wes Anderson's Milan | Day 42</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2015/11/10/wes-andersons-milan-day-42/</link>
  <pubDate>Tue, 10 Nov 2015 10:00:08 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1415</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[If you've ever dreamed of being in a Wes Anderson film, one way you can realize that dream is by visiting the cafe that Wes Anderson designed himselfâ <a href="http://www.fondazioneprada.org/barluce-en/?lang=en">Bar Luce</a>.Â I only spent time in Milan because I found out about this cafe and decided I'd fit it into my itinerary. It's not very often that I read an article and can conclude that well, I'll just makeÂ a pit stop there in a coupleÂ months.

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/1a9ff15e-7e50-4189-8c4f-adc733057f08-copy.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1418" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/1a9ff15e-7e50-4189-8c4f-adc733057f08-copy.jpg?w=660" alt="1A9FF15E-7E50-4189-8C4F-ADC733057F08 copy" width="660" height="495" /></a>

The cafe is located inÂ <a href="http://www.fondazioneprada.org/visit/visit-milan/?lang=en">Fondazione Prada</a>Â in Milan, whichÂ features a very clean, futuristicÂ design that resembles the setting for a post-apocalyptic sci-fi movie.Â The space provided a cold atmosphere, compared to the warm setting of a Wes Anderson film. I wondered if I was even in the right place. The only indicator of the cafe is the simple three-letter word: Bar, on its exterior.Â If you didn't come here looking for this cafe, you would have missed it if you weren't compelled toÂ grab a drink.

Bar Luce lives up to your Wes Anderson expectations. Everything in the cafe is visually appealingâ the food, the menu, the wallpaper, the restrooms. Everything. Although trying to take a symmetrical photo, as you would want to in a Wes Anderson setting,Â can be difficult. He did design the space to function. I enjoyed a Marocchino and Tiramisu, which I'm now realizing both include cocoa, coffee and dairy. Guess I had a theme going for my Wes Anderson experience.

After leaving Fondazione Prada, I went to theÂ <a href="http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g187849-d194970-Reviews-Navigli_District-Milan_Lombardy.html">Navigli District</a>,Â ordered some fried seafood (the best calamari and mediocre other sea creatures), grabbed a cheap bottle of beer, and sat along the canal and watched the sunset, as the buskers across the way played guitar and sang songs out of the 90s. I was also reminded thatÂ those friendly Italian mosquitoesÂ were still alive and thriving and still in love with my blood, all night. I had no expectations for Milan, but the night in Navigli District proved to be fun for drinking in the streets and people watching. Even managed to end my night with a slice of pizza.Â <em>Mmm, pizza.</em>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl4wp.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1424 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/pradawp.jpg" alt="pradawp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl4wp.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1420 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl4wp.jpg" alt="bl4wp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl3wp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1421" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl3wp.jpg?w=300" alt="bl3wp" width="300" height="225" /></a>Â  <a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl2wp.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-1422" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl2wp.jpg?w=300" alt="bl2wp" width="300" height="225" /></a>

<a href="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl1wp.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1423 size-full" src="https://janteziarra.files.wordpress.com/2015/11/bl1wp.jpg" alt="bl1wp" width="600" height="450" /></a>

<item>
  <title>But We'll Always Have Paris</title>
  <link>http://janteziarra.com/2016/02/13/but-well-always-have-paris/</link>
  <pubDate>Sat, 13 Feb 2016 07:24:50 +0000</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>janteziarra</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">http://janteziarra.com/?p=1496</guid>
  <description/>
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[They say Paris is the city of love, and it is, even if only a mirage. It is easy to fall in love in Paris, the city is rich with history and is romanticized through proper marketing. You have the Eiffel Tower, the Louvre, Pont des Arts and Notre Dame. These attractions were worth seeing, but my heart was in Montmarte, where the fabulous life of the fictional character AmÃ©lie Poulain resides. Maybe I should've known for that very reason that when I left Paris, the smoke and mirrors and camera tricks would stop working and any sort of summer romance would too when I left the city.

I thought Paris would be overrated, but it wasn't. I fell for the egg, cheese and bacon crÃªpes that I made into a breakfast staple and the speculoos macarons. CafÃ© des 2 Moulins and crÃ¨me brÃ»lÃ©e. The eclectic street art amongst pathways. The historyÂ of the city knowing great writers and artists of our time once thrived in this very city.

One late night while walking the streets of Paris, I was approached by a woman speaking to me in French. I responded with "je ne..." struggling to say <em>je ne comprends pasÂ </em>to tell her I don't understand, but anxiety lies in my ability to speak a different language and I couldn't spit it out. "Oh, American?" she said. She spoke in English and said she was liked my outfit, is a stylist, and askedÂ what brand my jacket was. I felt rather accomplished, complimented on my attire in the city known for its fashion, especially with my backpacker wardrobe.

Despite the reputation, the French were some of the nicest people I've met. I was even inspired to learn French again.

J'adore Paris, even if good beer is hard to find. Hey, at least they have good food!
